201
00:07:09,510 --> 00:07:10,600
So, what is dialectics?

202
00:07:10,630 --> 00:07:13,860
That's something
we'd need ten volumes to answer,

203
00:07:13,880 --> 00:07:15,120
but I'll try and summarize.

204
00:07:15,160 --> 00:07:17,370
First of all,
Hegelian dialectics

205
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:22,080
was opposed to another
philosophical method called metaphysics,

206
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:24,720
which was the dominant
philosophical method up to Hegel.

207
00:07:24,790 --> 00:07:26,520
In order for us to understand dialectics

208
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:29,400
it's worth it to understand
what metaphysics is

209
00:07:29,450 --> 00:07:31,520
because one thing
makes the other clearer.

210
00:07:31,580 --> 00:07:34,890
That's the part of the stream
where I'll cite the most, OK?

211
00:07:34,890 --> 00:07:36,690
I'll avoid reading
too many quotations

212
00:07:36,720 --> 00:07:38,940
but I think these ones are helpful

213
00:07:38,940 --> 00:07:40,940
because this part is
quite difficult.

214
00:07:40,970 --> 00:07:41,410
Right then,

215
00:07:41,430 --> 00:07:43,900
we’ve said that dialectics
opposes metaphysics.

216
00:07:43,950 --> 00:07:45,480
Engels:
"To the metaphysician,

217
00:07:45,710 --> 00:07:48,130
things and their mental reflexes,

218
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:52,990
ideas, are isolated, are to be considered
one after the other and apart from each other,

219
00:07:53,380 --> 00:07:58,590
are objects of investigation fixed, rigid,

220
00:07:58,700 --> 00:08:00,950
given once for all.

221
00:08:02,890 --> 00:08:05,520
He thinks in absolutely
irreconcilable antitheses

222
00:08:05,880 --> 00:08:07,580
His communication is

223
00:08:07,650 --> 00:08:11,890
'yea, yea; nay, nay'; for whatsoever
is more than these cometh of evil

224
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:14,840
For him, a thing either
exists or does not exist;

225
00:08:15,150 --> 00:08:18,440
a thing cannot at the same time
be itself and something else.

226
00:08:18,820 --> 00:08:22,190
Positive and negative
absolutely exclude one another".

227
00:08:22,270 --> 00:08:24,160
That's metaphysics then.

228
00:08:24,190 --> 00:08:25,120
In summary:

229
00:08:25,390 --> 00:08:29,730
metaphysics is a method
that works with isolated,

230
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:32,040
fixed categories.

231
00:08:32,100 --> 00:08:34,550
Dialectics, on the other hand,
another quote from Engels:

232
00:08:34,580 --> 00:08:37,550
"...comprehends things
and their representations,

233
00:08:37,820 --> 00:08:41,360
ideas,
in their essential connection,

234
00:08:41,650 --> 00:08:44,090
concatenation,

235
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:45,870
motion,

236
00:08:46,010 --> 00:08:48,930
origin
and ending.

237
00:08:49,190 --> 00:08:53,360
Such processes as those mentioned above are,
therefore, so many corroborations

238
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:55,410
of its own
method of procedure".

239
00:08:55,470 --> 00:08:58,270
That's referring to
passages from the book I'm quoting

240
00:08:58,270 --> 00:09:00,740
"Socialism: Utopian and Scientific"
by Engels.

241
00:09:00,770 --> 00:09:02,710
Dialectics is the philosophy

242
00:09:02,740 --> 00:09:06,130
that works
with constantly moving categories

243
00:09:06,160 --> 00:09:08,490
that relate to each other

244
00:09:08,510 --> 00:09:11,890
by means
of contradictions, or contraries.

245
00:09:11,960 --> 00:09:14,380
So, a famous example
Hegel gives is

246
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:16,690
the master-slave dialectics.

247
00:09:16,730 --> 00:09:20,380
In summary, the master can exist
only if there is a slave.

248
00:09:20,430 --> 00:09:21,520
Master and slave

249
00:09:21,530 --> 00:09:24,090
aren't fixed, isolated,
unchanging categories.

250
00:09:24,120 --> 00:09:25,480
The category of master

251
00:09:25,550 --> 00:09:28,050
only exists through
the existence of the slave category.

252
00:09:28,120 --> 00:09:30,990
Within the contradictions
between master and slave.

253
00:09:31,010 --> 00:09:33,680
These categories
change throughout history

254
00:09:33,720 --> 00:09:36,230
but I won't get too much into
the master-slave dialectics.

255
00:09:36,250 --> 00:09:40,200
I'm just showing you
how the categories that dialectics works upon

256
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:43,780
are interconnected
and ever-changing.

257
00:09:43,860 --> 00:09:44,250
That's it then.

258
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:46,570
So, according to Engels,
and I think that's a good analogy:

259
00:09:46,630 --> 00:09:50,270
Metaphysics cannot see the woods
for it is worried about the trees.

260
00:09:50,350 --> 00:09:51,310
For him and for Marx,

261
00:09:51,350 --> 00:09:53,680
dialectics was
much more adequate

262
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:56,400
for understanding
not only natural sciences' phenomena,

263
00:09:56,440 --> 00:09:57,860
but also society's.

264
00:09:57,910 --> 00:10:01,210
An example of dialectics
Engels gives in this book I quoted

265
00:10:01,420 --> 00:10:03,740
is Darwin's
theory of evolution.

266
00:10:03,850 --> 00:10:07,500
Darwin's theory of evolution
was a huge blow to metaphysics

267
00:10:07,550 --> 00:10:10,380
because it works
with transformation,

268
00:10:10,380 --> 00:10:13,260
with historical change
in the very long term.

269
00:10:13,350 --> 00:10:16,510
It made it impossible
to work with fixed categories,

270
00:10:16,550 --> 00:10:18,200
categories
are now changing.

271
00:10:18,290 --> 00:10:19,870
They transform,

272
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:23,010
they emerge and come to pass
as History goes on.

273
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:26,070
That's the dialectical principle
of Marx's philosophy,

274
00:10:26,220 --> 00:10:28,270
which is influenced by Hegel.

275
00:10:28,330 --> 00:10:32,010
Let's go to the other part then,
it was dialectical and historical materialism

276
00:10:32,070 --> 00:10:35,200
Let's talk materialism.
Materialism.

277
00:10:35,310 --> 00:10:37,440
I want you to do
a mental exercise now.

278
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:39,310
Look around you,
wherever you are.

279
00:10:39,430 --> 00:10:41,500
Look around.
Look at everything that surrounds you.

280
00:10:41,700 --> 00:10:43,690
Look if there's
a table nearby, a computer,

281
00:10:43,790 --> 00:10:45,460
a cellphone,
a chair,

282
00:10:45,640 --> 00:10:46,990
anything.

283
00:10:47,030 --> 00:10:48,250
I want you to think about this:

284
00:10:48,290 --> 00:10:50,470
who made these things?
Who manufactured them?

285
00:10:50,510 --> 00:10:52,630
If there's a chair where you are,
who manufactured it?

286
00:10:52,660 --> 00:10:54,250
If there's a couch,
who made that couch?

287
00:10:54,260 --> 00:10:56,170
And further,
who transported it there?

288
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:57,530
If the couch has metal parts,

289
00:10:57,600 --> 00:10:59,760
who mined the metals?

290
00:10:59,810 --> 00:11:02,520
Whose hands extracted them
from the veins of the earth?

291
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:03,880
Now I want you to reflect

292
00:11:03,950 --> 00:11:05,510
on how little we think about that.

293
00:11:05,540 --> 00:11:06,850
How little we think

294
00:11:07,100 --> 00:11:09,860
about who made
the objects that surround us.

295
00:11:09,910 --> 00:11:11,700
And no, guys,
it wasn't machined,

296
00:11:11,730 --> 00:11:12,710
it wasn't just machines.

297
00:11:12,810 --> 00:11:16,940
We are surrounded by
an immense amount of human labor.

298
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:18,260
But we don't realize it.

299
00:11:18,280 --> 00:11:22,260
We're disconnected
from the human labor that surrounds us.

300
00:11:22,290 --> 00:11:28,072
Materialism is the understanding

301
00:11:28,070 --> 00:11:32,608
that material production is
the basis for our social structure.

302
00:11:32,640 --> 00:11:36,400
Not only do we have to think about
who made what is around us

303
00:11:36,440 --> 00:11:37,980
but what surrounds us is

304
00:11:38,030 --> 00:11:42,130
the basis upon
which we organize society.

305
00:11:42,190 --> 00:11:44,880
The two things are connected.

306
00:11:44,930 --> 00:11:46,520
That's materialism's
great trump card.

307
00:11:46,520 --> 00:11:48,080
Let's go back to Hegel for a bit.

308
00:11:48,090 --> 00:11:49,750
Marx incorporated
Hegel's dialectics.

309
00:11:49,770 --> 00:11:53,220
But materialism arises
from a critique of Hegel.

310
00:11:53,290 --> 00:11:57,910
A critique of what exactly?
Hegel was an idealist.

311
00:11:57,950 --> 00:12:01,150
Remember I said Marxism
came around as a critique of idealism?

312
00:12:01,250 --> 00:12:05,390
And this critique of idealism
is mainly a critique of Hegel's philosophy.

313
00:12:05,420 --> 00:12:09,490
So, Marx takes Hegelian dialectics
but leaves out idealism.

314
00:12:09,550 --> 00:12:11,200
Let's use a quotation
from Marx himself then:

315
00:12:11,250 --> 00:12:17,000
“My dialectic method is
not only different from the Hegelian,

316
00:12:17,040 --> 00:12:19,200
but is its direct opposite.

317
00:12:19,230 --> 00:12:21,580
To Hegel, the life-process of the human brain,
i.e., the process of thinking,

318
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:23,970
which, under the name of ‘the Idea,’
(with a capital “I”)

319
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:25,970
he even transforms
into an independent subject,

320
00:12:26,050 --> 00:12:28,770
is the demiurges
(for those who don't know, demiurges means deity)

321
00:12:28,810 --> 00:12:32,730
and the real world is only the external,
phenomenal form of ‘the Idea.’

322
00:12:32,750 --> 00:12:35,800
With me, on the contrary, the ideal is
nothing else than the material world

323
00:12:35,850 --> 00:12:38,290
reflected by the human mind,
and translated into forms of thought".

324
00:12:38,290 --> 00:12:39,450
That's a quotation from Capital.

325
00:12:39,450 --> 00:12:41,730
Don't worry,
I know it's complicated but I'll explain.

326
00:12:41,790 --> 00:12:45,860
For Hegel, the reality is
a manifestation of human ideas,

327
00:12:45,890 --> 00:12:48,080
a manifestation of
human thought.

328
00:12:48,110 --> 00:12:50,080
And human thought in its turn

329
00:12:50,110 --> 00:12:53,190
is the manifestation of the original Idea
(With a capital “I”)

330
00:12:53,190 --> 00:12:56,250
that comes
from the deity, from God.

331
00:12:56,280 --> 00:12:58,910
Hegel's philosophy
has a theological outlook.

332
00:12:58,960 --> 00:13:01,620
And the Young Hegelians
were also idealists.

333
00:13:01,660 --> 00:13:04,800
They believed that
what prevented society's development

334
00:13:04,850 --> 00:13:06,510
were the ideas
in people's minds.

335
00:13:06,550 --> 00:13:09,400
There needed to be
a revolution in people's thought

336
00:13:09,440 --> 00:13:11,890
and only then
from reason and thought

337
00:13:12,030 --> 00:13:13,350
we would transform reality.

338
00:13:13,400 --> 00:13:14,460
More than that,

339
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,330
as capitalism developed

340
00:13:16,350 --> 00:13:19,330
there appeared philosophers
that saw what was happening,

341
00:13:19,420 --> 00:13:21,590
the rise of poverty,
misery,

342
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:24,660
and devised fairer,
more egalitarian societies

343
00:13:24,680 --> 00:13:28,280
that would free all of humanity.

344
00:13:28,580 --> 00:13:29,230
Where?

345
00:13:29,520 --> 00:13:30,310
In their minds.

346
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:33,220
According to Engels,
the more detailed these societies were,

347
00:13:33,230 --> 00:13:36,370
the further they drifted from reality.

348
00:13:36,420 --> 00:13:40,560
These philosophers became known
as Utopian socialists.

349
00:13:40,590 --> 00:13:42,700
For those who don't know,
utopia is a 'non-place'

350
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:45,270
Idealism means
you create an idea in your head

351
00:13:45,390 --> 00:13:47,190
and try to apply it to reality.

352
00:13:47,230 --> 00:13:48,910
Materialism
is the opposite of that.

353
00:13:48,960 --> 00:13:50,830
Marx puts this idea
upside-down.

354
00:13:50,830 --> 00:13:53,840
It's not reality
that is created by our thoughts.

355
00:13:53,870 --> 00:13:57,320
But rather our ideas are
an abstraction of reality.

356
00:13:57,360 --> 00:13:59,520
First, we get into
contact with reality

357
00:13:59,540 --> 00:14:02,100
and then we formulate ideas,
not the contrary.

358
00:14:02,160 --> 00:14:05,320
And there is
an inseparable connection

359
00:14:05,350 --> 00:14:06,280
inseparable

360
00:14:06,300 --> 00:14:09,150
between material reality,

361
00:14:09,540 --> 00:14:11,340
the objects that are around us,

362
00:14:11,520 --> 00:14:14,340
and how
we organize society.

363
00:14:14,380 --> 00:14:17,330
These two things
are inseparable.

364
00:14:17,370 --> 00:14:21,690
There's no social organization
without a material backing,

365
00:14:21,730 --> 00:14:23,150
a material substrate.

366
00:14:23,170 --> 00:14:26,920
There's no use
in designing a society in our heads

367
00:14:26,920 --> 00:14:29,110
and trying
to apply it to reality

368
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:31,430
while ignoring reality itself.

369
00:14:31,470 --> 00:14:34,020
That's materialism.
That's the difference, right?

370
00:14:34,080 --> 00:14:36,610
So, what is material reality?
To make it clearer,

371
00:14:36,640 --> 00:14:38,310
it's not only nature,

372
00:14:38,340 --> 00:14:40,010
but also the way we produce

373
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:41,500
Remember
I told you to look around?

374
00:14:41,510 --> 00:14:45,100
That is all produced in order to
satisfy our material needs.

375
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:47,020
We have to sit down;
we make a chair.

376
00:14:47,070 --> 00:14:49,200
That's part of
material reality as well.

377
00:14:49,240 --> 00:14:50,060
But not only that,

378
00:14:50,080 --> 00:14:51,970
our production also satisfies

379
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,110
our cultural
and intellectual cravings.

380
00:14:54,160 --> 00:14:56,400
Not only eating,
clothing, housing

381
00:14:56,400 --> 00:14:59,440
but also what we desire
to consume as culture.

382
00:14:59,470 --> 00:15:01,660
This quote is
by Marx and Engels:

383
00:15:01,680 --> 00:15:04,770
"What they [the individuals] are,
therefore, coincides with their production,

384
00:15:04,800 --> 00:15:07,470
both with what they produce
and with how they produce.

385
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:09,880
The nature of individuals thus
depends on the material conditions

386
00:15:09,940 --> 00:15:11,600
determining their production."

387
00:15:11,620 --> 00:15:15,840
What we are depends
on how we produce our existence.

388
00:15:15,890 --> 00:15:17,770
What we are depends on
how we eat,

389
00:15:17,790 --> 00:15:19,520
where we live,
what we wear,

390
00:15:19,590 --> 00:15:21,080
on how we wear.
It depends on that,

391
00:15:21,130 --> 00:15:24,300
on how we transport ourselves,
how we satisfy our needs.

392
00:15:24,310 --> 00:15:27,040
So, the way
we produce reality,

393
00:15:27,060 --> 00:15:29,310
we call it
infrastructure.

394
00:15:29,340 --> 00:15:33,980
Our infrastructure is the production
of food, of clothing, of houses, etc.

395
00:15:34,060 --> 00:15:38,890
A social structure arises
over this infrastructure.

396
00:15:38,920 --> 00:15:40,890
We call that
superstructure.

397
00:15:41,090 --> 00:15:42,630
It's what is above the infrastructure.

398
00:15:42,670 --> 00:15:47,290
What is there in the superstructure?
Culture, religion, morals, among other things.

399
00:15:47,320 --> 00:15:48,960
That is, our culture,

400
00:15:49,180 --> 00:15:50,200
our religion,

401
00:15:50,360 --> 00:15:51,030
our morals,

402
00:15:51,100 --> 00:15:52,560
are all above.

403
00:15:52,810 --> 00:15:56,700
They are built upon a material basis.

404
00:15:56,750 --> 00:15:58,140
That is to say,

405
00:15:58,180 --> 00:16:00,670
for example,
that our religion has everything to do

406
00:16:00,690 --> 00:16:03,700
with how we produce
our material reality,

407
00:16:03,720 --> 00:16:05,550
how we produce our food,

408
00:16:05,640 --> 00:16:07,200
our houses,
our clothes.

409
00:16:07,220 --> 00:16:09,700
That is all connected

410
00:16:09,740 --> 00:16:14,440
And we can never lose sight of
the material basis of reality.

411
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:16,910
One thing depends on the other.

412
00:16:17,060 --> 00:16:19,140
Is this
a mechanical process, though?

413
00:16:19,180 --> 00:16:22,190
Does that mean that every time
we produce food in the same way

414
00:16:22,190 --> 00:16:23,480
the same religion will emerge?

415
00:16:23,480 --> 00:16:24,140
No,

416
00:16:24,190 --> 00:16:28,410
it doesn't mean that the same material basis
will give rise to the same superstructure,

417
00:16:28,440 --> 00:16:33,290
but that the superstructure
is dependent on the material basis.

418
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:34,650
Dependent.

419
00:16:34,690 --> 00:16:37,310
It is not mechanically
determined by it,

420
00:16:37,350 --> 00:16:38,660
but dependent on it.

421
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:39,950
This is really important;

422
00:16:39,970 --> 00:16:42,330
once this superstructure has risen,

423
00:16:42,350 --> 00:16:45,620
it impacts back
on the material basis.

424
00:16:45,620 --> 00:16:48,680
So, our culture,
our religion, our morals

425
00:16:48,850 --> 00:16:51,410
can impact
on how we produce our reality.

426
00:16:51,430 --> 00:16:53,060
But it doesn't exist
without that reality.

427
00:16:53,110 --> 00:16:55,450
That's a dialectical movement.

428
00:16:55,460 --> 00:16:57,090
Remember we said
dialectics was important?

429
00:16:57,120 --> 00:16:58,970
In its connections,
in its movement,

430
00:16:58,990 --> 00:17:00,160
and not in fixed categories.

431
00:17:00,190 --> 00:17:03,140
Infrastructure and superstructure
aren't fixed, unchanging categories.

432
00:17:03,140 --> 00:17:05,630
They are connected,
they interact with each other and they move.

433
00:17:05,680 --> 00:17:06,730
I know it's complicated,

434
00:17:06,770 --> 00:17:07,810
but give it a chance

435
00:17:07,900 --> 00:17:10,040
and at least
get familiarized with this vocabulary:

436
00:17:10,070 --> 00:17:14,000
materialism, material basis, infrastructure,
superstructure, dialectics, etc.

437
00:17:14,020 --> 00:17:15,900
Remember it was
dialectical and historical materialism?

438
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:17,210
Where does
the historical part come in?

439
00:17:17,240 --> 00:17:20,050
This method is such that
Marx and Engels perceive History

440
00:17:20,050 --> 00:17:23,960
through the ways people produced
their reality in order to satisfy their needs

441
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,520
and how that affected
the social structure.

442
00:17:26,550 --> 00:17:28,090
So, for Marx and Engels

443
00:17:28,110 --> 00:17:31,990
the first historical fact is
the satisfaction of our needs.

444
00:17:32,030 --> 00:17:34,670
The first time
a human built a tool

445
00:17:34,780 --> 00:17:37,970
in order to satisfy a need.
That's the first historical fact.

446
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:41,350
From the moment we satisfy
a need on, we create other needs.

447
00:17:41,400 --> 00:17:45,190
This is the historical process
of creating new needs.

448
00:17:45,210 --> 00:17:46,690
The wheel of History
keeps on turning

449
00:17:46,690 --> 00:17:49,080
as we satisfy our needs.

450
00:17:49,100 --> 00:17:50,660
Marx and Engels
look at History

451
00:17:50,850 --> 00:17:52,060
and ask:
how did they produce?

452
00:17:52,100 --> 00:17:54,980
From this production,
what was the social structure?

453
00:17:55,040 --> 00:17:57,370
How does the social structure
of said society

454
00:17:57,420 --> 00:17:59,780
relate to the way
this society produces?

455
00:17:59,820 --> 00:18:01,110
That's historical materialism.

456
00:18:01,150 --> 00:18:03,580
For summarizing,
there's a quotation that's a bit long,

457
00:18:03,630 --> 00:18:05,190
but it ties together
everything I've said.

458
00:18:05,230 --> 00:18:10,270
"The materialist conception of history starts
from the proposition that the production.

459
00:18:10,420 --> 00:18:15,210
of the means to support human life and, next
to production, the exchange of things produced,

460
00:18:15,940 --> 00:18:19,230
is the basis of all social structure;
that in every society

461
00:18:19,420 --> 00:18:22,440
that has appeared in history,
the manner in which wealth is distributed and

462
00:18:22,480 --> 00:18:25,570
society divided into classes or orders

463
00:18:25,590 --> 00:18:29,310
is dependent upon
what is produced, how it is produced,

464
00:18:29,450 --> 00:18:31,710
and how the products
are exchanged.

465
00:18:32,090 --> 00:18:33,370
From this point of view,

466
00:18:33,510 --> 00:18:36,550
the final causes of
all social changes

467
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:38,300
and political revolutions

468
00:18:38,300 --> 00:18:41,630
are to be sought,
not in men's brains,

469
00:18:41,670 --> 00:18:46,030
not in men's better insights
into eternal truth and justice,

470
00:18:46,090 --> 00:18:49,980
but in changes in the modes
of production and exchange.

471
00:18:50,020 --> 00:18:56,580
They are to be sought, not in the philosophy,
but in the economics of each particular epoch."

472
00:18:56,640 --> 00:19:00,160
This means that revolutions,
including the bourgeois revolutions,

473
00:19:00,200 --> 00:19:03,500
didn't happen in the way
liberals themselves describe them.

474
00:19:03,530 --> 00:19:07,070
The liberals say people started
demanding more freedom

475
00:19:07,100 --> 00:19:09,710
and that propelled
the revolution forward.

476
00:19:09,770 --> 00:19:11,260
No. Revolutions happen

477
00:19:11,260 --> 00:19:14,400
when our way of producing
and reproducing life changes.

478
00:19:14,400 --> 00:19:18,840
Every revolution has
a material basis, a material substrate.

479
00:19:18,870 --> 00:19:24,630
It doesn't appear in someone's mind and is then
applied to reality because that's impossible,

480
00:19:24,760 --> 00:19:26,850
that goes against
the laws of nature.

481
00:19:26,890 --> 00:19:30,110
And that's what we call idealism.

482
00:19:30,110 --> 00:19:35,670
Marxism emerges as an opposition,
as a critique of idealism and utopianism.

483
00:19:35,670 --> 00:19:38,500
OK? Pay attention to
this last Engel's quote here:

484
00:19:38,540 --> 00:19:43,110
"They are to be sought,
not in the philosophy, but in the economics.”

485
00:19:43,140 --> 00:19:45,510
That's what we are going to talk about now:
the Critique of Economy.

486
00:19:45,530 --> 00:19:47,510
So, one thing that I need you
to pay attention to is this:

487
00:19:47,510 --> 00:19:49,510
Why did I first explain through
the philosophical pillar?

488
00:19:49,560 --> 00:19:51,580
The philosophical pillar
gives us the method.

489
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:56,340
And Marx and Engels analyze everything
from now using this method.

490
00:19:56,400 --> 00:20:00,060
Dialectical and historical materialism
is always the perspective.

491
00:20:00,100 --> 00:20:03,520
This method is applied to reality
to understand reality.

492
00:20:03,560 --> 00:20:06,750
And now we move on to
the economic pillar of Marxism.

493
00:20:06,790 --> 00:20:07,160
Let's do it!

494
00:20:07,180 --> 00:20:10,060
Remember I said that Marx
was exiled to France and he met Engels there?

495
00:20:10,100 --> 00:20:13,920
So, Engels read Marx's texts
and he criticized Marx's texts

496
00:20:13,920 --> 00:20:17,650
He said: “Marx, there is an economic dimension
missing from your analyses”

497
00:20:17,670 --> 00:20:20,240
Then Marx closed himself
inside a library

498
00:20:20,270 --> 00:20:23,650
and read the writings
of English economists,

499
00:20:23,760 --> 00:20:25,320
especially these two on the screen:

500
00:20:25,340 --> 00:20:27,680
Adam Smith and David Ricardo.

501
00:20:27,710 --> 00:20:29,400
And I need to clarify now:

502
00:20:29,440 --> 00:20:32,320
Can you see that I'm using the term
"Political Economy"

503
00:20:32,340 --> 00:20:34,880
Back then,
"Political Economy" term was dominant

504
00:20:34,930 --> 00:20:39,350
because it was clear that
