521
00:21:22,470 --> 00:21:25,040
And some would say,
just to make it clear for you,

522
00:21:25,080 --> 00:21:28,530
some would say
there is no Marxist Economics,

523
00:21:28,540 --> 00:21:31,160
that Marxist Economics is
the bourgeois economy's critique,

524
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:33,230
but you'll see controversy about it .

525
00:21:33,280 --> 00:21:34,740
Just to let you know
that this exists.

526
00:21:34,780 --> 00:21:37,290
What is the critique of
Marx's Political Economy?

527
00:21:37,290 --> 00:21:40,290
It's an analysis of capitalism,
basically.

528
00:21:40,290 --> 00:21:43,410
Marx lived at a time
when capitalism was already dominant.

529
00:21:43,420 --> 00:21:45,890
But what is capitalism, folks?
What is capitalism?

530
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:46,990
And I'm telling you,

531
00:21:46,990 --> 00:21:48,990
this Critique of
Political Economy's excerpt

532
00:21:48,990 --> 00:21:51,610
will be where
I'll inject you with

533
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:55,710
mandatory vocabulary to understand
Critique of Political Economy, OK?

534
00:21:55,710 --> 00:21:59,800
Here we are going to make
a kind of glossary because it's needed, right?

535
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:02,900
To truly understand; to know how to describe
what these terms mean.

536
00:22:02,930 --> 00:22:05,720
I'm going to talk like that,
with just the cam, and we'll recap later.

537
00:22:05,800 --> 00:22:06,590
Anyway, relax.

538
00:22:06,640 --> 00:22:07,440
What is capitalism?

539
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:11,480
Capitalism is a mode of production, mode of production.

540
00:22:11,510 --> 00:22:12,930
What is a "mode of production"?

541
00:22:12,970 --> 00:22:21,490
It's the result of interactions between
productive forces and relations of production.

542
00:22:21,490 --> 00:22:24,100
What are productive forces
and relations of production?

543
00:22:24,150 --> 00:22:28,760
Productive forces are
how humans act on nature.

544
00:22:28,810 --> 00:22:33,830
Relations of production are
how humans act on each other.

545
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:38,670
Therefore, we actuate
on nature and each other

546
00:22:38,720 --> 00:22:45,520
The interaction between these actions
results in the mode of production, right?

547
00:22:45,520 --> 00:22:48,610
Point number one:
What are the capitalist productive forces?

548
00:22:48,630 --> 00:22:51,180
Capitalist productive forces are

549
00:22:51,390 --> 00:22:57,280
the employment of industry, machinery,
automation of energy matrices

550
00:22:57,280 --> 00:23:04,490
and especially division of labor.

551
00:23:04,520 --> 00:23:08,430
In Capitalism,
our work is segmented,

552
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:12,930
it is broken down into
small specialized parts.

553
00:23:12,970 --> 00:23:16,860
Therefore, our capitalist productive force
isn't just a machine,

554
00:23:17,120 --> 00:23:19,680
but it's how we divide up this work.

555
00:23:19,680 --> 00:23:21,840
What are the relations of production?

556
00:23:21,860 --> 00:23:24,950
We talked about productive forces,
now we have relations of production.

557
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:26,890
Capitalist relations of production

558
00:23:26,920 --> 00:23:32,750
are based on the exploitation of proletarian
labor by the bourgeoisie, OK?

559
00:23:32,800 --> 00:23:38,690
The foundation
of the relations of production is exploitation.

560
00:23:38,850 --> 00:23:42,010
We are going to
explain about exploitation further ahead.

561
00:23:42,050 --> 00:23:44,010
First of all,

562
00:23:44,100 --> 00:23:48,950
that exploitation is based
on a class division.

563
00:23:48,990 --> 00:23:50,730
What is class?

564
00:23:50,770 --> 00:23:55,190
Class, folks,
is a social division of labor.

565
00:23:55,250 --> 00:23:57,800
Are there classless societies?
Yes.

566
00:23:57,840 --> 00:24:01,190
In classless societies
everyone has to work,

567
00:24:01,220 --> 00:24:03,680
everyone benefits
from the fruits of labor,

568
00:24:03,720 --> 00:24:07,140
and the labor is divided
by ability or skill.

569
00:24:07,180 --> 00:24:10,640
This type of division
we call "Natural Division".

570
00:24:10,700 --> 00:24:13,270
In class societies,

571
00:24:13,310 --> 00:24:16,260
there is no natural division,
there is a social division.

572
00:24:16,300 --> 00:24:17,110
And what does it means?

573
00:24:17,170 --> 00:24:18,660
Imagine that
you work in a factory.

574
00:24:18,690 --> 00:24:22,260
The factory owner isn't
less skilled than you to work in the factory.

575
00:24:22,290 --> 00:24:24,890
So, why do you work at the factory
and he doesn't?

576
00:24:24,940 --> 00:24:26,930
Since he has
the same skills as you.

577
00:24:26,980 --> 00:24:28,850
Because he belongs
to another class.

578
00:24:28,880 --> 00:24:33,130
What determines the class is which position
you occupy in the production chain.

579
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:36,910
And under capitalism,
these classes are increasingly comprised

580
00:24:36,980 --> 00:24:41,700
of the bourgeois, In other words, the class that
doesn't work and owns the means of production,

581
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:45,540
and proletariat, the class
that does work and owns nothing

582
00:24:45,570 --> 00:24:46,920
other than their work force.

583
00:24:46,990 --> 00:24:50,880
What divides these classes is
not skill, nor ability, not even vocation,

584
00:24:50,910 --> 00:24:51,810
it is a social division.

585
00:24:51,840 --> 00:24:54,350
Well then, another characteristic
of relations of production.

586
00:24:54,390 --> 00:24:55,470
We have classes

587
00:24:55,490 --> 00:24:58,130
and one of them owns
the means of production,

588
00:24:58,180 --> 00:25:03,080
that is, these means of production are
private property of someone.

589
00:25:03,110 --> 00:25:06,930
One of the central characteristics
of capitalism is the private property.

590
00:25:06,970 --> 00:25:08,730
What is private property?

591
00:25:08,770 --> 00:25:11,690
There is a classical definition
From the bourgeois economists themselves:

592
00:25:11,730 --> 00:25:16,790
Private property is
the free disposal of another's labor power

593
00:25:16,830 --> 00:25:18,540
When we are talking about
private property,

594
00:25:18,550 --> 00:25:22,610
we are talking about private property
of the means of production.

595
00:25:22,640 --> 00:25:26,130
Why did private property,
and only "private property",

596
00:25:26,170 --> 00:25:28,840
become synonymous with private property
of the means of production?

597
00:25:28,890 --> 00:25:31,060
Because the private property
of the means of production was

598
00:25:31,060 --> 00:25:33,230
the first form of private property.

599
00:25:33,300 --> 00:25:35,540
So, in the time of
Marx, Smith, and Ricardo,

600
00:25:35,560 --> 00:25:39,770
talking about private property meant
private property of the means of production.

601
00:25:39,820 --> 00:25:40,650
Back to definition:

602
00:25:40,670 --> 00:25:44,950
Private property is the free disposal
of another one's labor power.

603
00:25:45,020 --> 00:25:45,500
An example:

604
00:25:45,540 --> 00:25:46,875
remember that mode of production

605
00:25:46,900 --> 00:25:49,630
is the interaction between
productive force and relations of production?

606
00:25:49,630 --> 00:25:52,010
Did we have other modes of production?
Yes.

607
00:25:52,080 --> 00:25:54,270
We had, for example,
the feudal mode of production.

608
00:25:54,270 --> 00:25:57,240
We had, for example,
the slave-owning mode of production.

609
00:25:57,300 --> 00:25:59,080
For example,
in the slave-owning mode of production.

610
00:25:59,080 --> 00:26:01,350
What is private property
in the slave-owning mode of production?

611
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:01,880
The slave.

612
00:26:01,900 --> 00:26:05,150
Remember that private property is
the free disposal of another one's labor power?

613
00:26:05,200 --> 00:26:08,570
How does the slave owner dispose
of the labor force of others?

614
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:09,630
By owning the person

615
00:26:09,660 --> 00:26:13,560
Another person's work is
freely available to the slaveholder.

616
00:26:13,600 --> 00:26:16,570
The person is
the owner's private property.

617
00:26:16,620 --> 00:26:17,890
How this works in capitalism?

618
00:26:17,930 --> 00:26:20,570
People are not the property
of the capitalist,

619
00:26:20,640 --> 00:26:23,150
but the capitalist owns
the means of production.

620
00:26:23,180 --> 00:26:26,570
Means of production, that is,
what is necessary for executing labor

621
00:26:26,610 --> 00:26:28,570
is taken from the hand of workers,

622
00:26:28,610 --> 00:26:33,290
and the capitalists controls the worker's
productive forces through wage labor.

623
00:26:33,330 --> 00:26:36,630
Workers are forced to sell
their labor power

624
00:26:36,650 --> 00:26:39,480
to work on the means of production
that have been taken from their hands.

625
00:26:39,500 --> 00:26:41,680
And how this capitalist can take

626
00:26:41,680 --> 00:26:44,460
these means of production
out of the worker's hand?

627
00:26:44,610 --> 00:26:48,010
Because he owns
something called "Capital".

628
00:26:48,060 --> 00:26:49,270
What is capital?

629
00:26:49,310 --> 00:26:51,810
Capital can be summed up
in a simple few sentences

630
00:26:51,850 --> 00:26:53,610
"Capital is value that creates value";

631
00:26:53,640 --> 00:26:56,250
"resources that create resources";
"Wealth that creates wealth"

632
00:26:56,290 --> 00:26:58,140
Capital is money?
No.

633
00:26:58,190 --> 00:27:00,500
But capital can be money?
Yes.

634
00:27:00,620 --> 00:27:02,070
They aren't synonymous,
it's that what I mean.

635
00:27:02,110 --> 00:27:04,640
What you have
in your wallet now isn't capital, OK?

636
00:27:04,700 --> 00:27:07,670
Capital is a resource
that can be in form of money

637
00:27:07,670 --> 00:27:10,450
that is used
in the acquisition of means of production.

638
00:27:10,450 --> 00:27:14,180
Factory, machine, land,
energy, raw material

639
00:27:14,260 --> 00:27:15,770
and workforce.

640
00:27:15,800 --> 00:27:18,500
Once such means are acquired

641
00:27:18,700 --> 00:27:20,820
they become part of the capital.

642
00:27:20,870 --> 00:27:25,840
So, factory, machine, energy,
and raw material are part of the capital, OK?

643
00:27:25,880 --> 00:27:27,230
That's why capital
isn't just money.

644
00:27:27,230 --> 00:27:28,170
Therefore, in short,

645
00:27:28,190 --> 00:27:30,660
capitalist relations
of production are based

646
00:27:30,720 --> 00:27:33,650
on class division. One class
owns the means of production and doesn't work,

647
00:27:33,670 --> 00:27:37,600
and the other only owns
its own labor power and has to sell it.

648
00:27:37,630 --> 00:27:40,910
This brings us to the last characteristic
of relations of production:

649
00:27:40,960 --> 00:27:43,520
the Commodification
of Social Relations.

650
00:27:43,540 --> 00:27:49,440
In capitalism, the commodity
is the center of social relations.

651
00:27:49,490 --> 00:27:52,480
In capitalism,
we don't produce our existence,

652
00:27:52,530 --> 00:27:54,920
we buy our existence.

653
00:27:54,950 --> 00:27:57,680
You don't produce your food,
you buy your food.

654
00:27:57,730 --> 00:28:00,020
You don't sew your clothes,
you buy your clothes.

655
00:28:00,050 --> 00:28:02,470
You don't build your house,
you buy your house.

656
00:28:02,480 --> 00:28:05,470
And you sell
your labor force too,

657
00:28:05,510 --> 00:28:07,950
your labor force
becomes a commodity.

658
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:09,520
But what is a commodity?

659
00:28:09,550 --> 00:28:11,880
A Commodity is something that is produced
for someone else's consumption,

660
00:28:11,960 --> 00:28:13,350
and to be traded on the market.

661
00:28:13,350 --> 00:28:15,740
This commodity element
deserves more attention.

662
00:28:15,770 --> 00:28:16,720
Because, again,

663
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:20,090
as a commodity is the center
of all social relations in capitalism,

664
00:28:20,140 --> 00:28:21,290
it needs to be understood.

665
00:28:21,320 --> 00:28:24,290
Before that,
let's review everything.

666
00:28:24,290 --> 00:28:24,970
Vocabulary:

667
00:28:24,970 --> 00:28:28,920
Mode of Production: interaction between
productive forces and relations of production.

668
00:28:29,070 --> 00:28:30,920
Capitalism is a Mode of Production.

669
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:33,840
What are Productive Forces:
how humans act on nature.

670
00:28:33,880 --> 00:28:36,940
What are Relations of Production:
how humans act on each other.

671
00:28:36,980 --> 00:28:39,040
What is Class:
social division of labor

672
00:28:39,040 --> 00:28:40,880
(as opposed to the natural work division),

673
00:28:40,910 --> 00:28:43,240
position occupied
in the productive process.

674
00:28:43,280 --> 00:28:46,590
Is class determined
by how much money you make? No.

675
00:28:46,630 --> 00:28:49,560
If you earn wages,
you are a worker, OK?

676
00:28:49,650 --> 00:28:51,470
If you earn wages,
you are a proletariat.

677
00:28:51,510 --> 00:28:54,410
"Oh, my salary is 100k/month",
you are a proletariat.

678
00:28:54,460 --> 00:28:57,870
Class is determined
by the social division of labor.

679
00:28:57,890 --> 00:29:01,960
Class is determined
by where you are in the productive process.

680
00:29:01,960 --> 00:29:03,530
What makes it so confusing is

681
00:29:03,530 --> 00:29:07,510
that, nowadays, we use such terminology
as "upper class", "middle class",  "lower class".

682
00:29:07,510 --> 00:29:09,140
What determines class for Marxism is

683
00:29:09,170 --> 00:29:12,470
the position you occupy
in the productive process,

684
00:29:12,540 --> 00:29:13,620
Right? So that's right.

685
00:29:13,620 --> 00:29:17,860
Private Property:
free disposal of another's labor power.

686
00:29:17,880 --> 00:29:21,310
Remembering that we are talking about
the private property of means of production.

687
00:29:21,340 --> 00:29:23,960
It's not your house,
your old truck, or your flip-flops.

688
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:26,920
Means of production:
what is necessary for the execution of work.

689
00:29:26,980 --> 00:29:29,090
Factories, raw material, energy.

690
00:29:29,130 --> 00:29:31,190
Capital:
value that creates value,

691
00:29:31,220 --> 00:29:33,400
resource that creates resource,
wealth that creates wealth.

692
00:29:33,400 --> 00:29:36,610
Commodity: something produced
to be consumed by others,

693
00:29:36,690 --> 00:29:37,790
and to be sold in the market, okay?

694
00:29:37,830 --> 00:29:38,730
OK? Let's keep going!

695
00:29:38,760 --> 00:29:41,190
Let’s move on to a subject
that is a bit more complicated,

696
00:29:41,190 --> 00:29:45,030
but fundamental to our understanding
of Marx's critique of Political Economy.

697
00:29:45,060 --> 00:29:48,420
Remember that the commodity
is the center of our social relations?

698
00:29:48,440 --> 00:29:50,610
This commodity has
something called Value.

699
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:52,550
So, the question
that comes up is:

700
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:53,360
what is Value?

701
00:29:53,390 --> 00:29:55,120
How is Value determined?

702
00:29:55,120 --> 00:29:56,560
OK, so I'll begin with a quote

703
00:29:56,560 --> 00:29:59,080
hat made me understand Value
once and for all.

704
00:29:59,110 --> 00:30:01,670
But I'll start with the quote
and then we are gonna describe Value,

705
00:30:01,670 --> 00:30:02,360
not the contrary.

706
00:30:02,430 --> 00:30:04,470
"...if I say a quarter of wheat

707
00:30:04,490 --> 00:30:06,000
(quarter is a unit of measure)

708
00:30:06,210 --> 00:30:09,180
exchanges with iron
in a certain proportion,

709
00:30:09,350 --> 00:30:14,090
or the Value of a quarter of wheat is
expressed in  a  certain  amount  of  iron,

710
00:30:14,310 --> 00:30:16,820
I say that the Value of wheat
and its equivalent in iron

711
00:30:16,910 --> 00:30:20,840
are equal
to some third thing,

712
00:30:20,940 --> 00:30:22,740
which is neither
wheat nor iron,

713
00:30:22,910 --> 00:30:27,550
because I suppose them to express
the same magnitude in two different shapes.

714
00:30:27,580 --> 00:30:29,900
Either of them,

715
00:30:30,050 --> 00:30:31,670
the wheat or the iron,

716
00:30:31,670 --> 00:30:34,900
must, therefore,
independently of the other, be reducible

717
00:30:34,920 --> 00:30:36,230
to this third thing

718
00:30:36,270 --> 00:30:37,950
which is their common measure."

719
00:30:37,950 --> 00:30:39,660
I've never forgotten this quote.

720
00:30:39,690 --> 00:30:42,300
If a certain amount of wheat
is equal to a certain amount of iron,

721
00:30:42,300 --> 00:30:46,250
it does not mean that one is the same as the other,
but that they are equal to a third thing.

722
00:30:46,260 --> 00:30:49,530
And this third thing is Value.

723
00:30:49,560 --> 00:30:50,640
OK, so,
Value.

724
00:30:50,660 --> 00:30:53,390
Value is maybe one of the most complicated
concepts of Political Economy,

725
00:30:53,390 --> 00:30:55,020
even Marx recognized that.

726
00:30:55,040 --> 00:30:56,510
Marx says
in the Introduction to Capital

727
00:30:56,510 --> 00:30:59,810
that the first chapter was the most complicated,
and it is the one in which he describes Value

728
00:30:59,850 --> 00:31:01,530
We have
commodities in society,

729
00:31:01,580 --> 00:31:02,800
we buy our things.

730
00:31:02,830 --> 00:31:04,110
These commodities have Value.

731
00:31:04,140 --> 00:31:06,440
Do you remember
when I told you to look around?

732
00:31:06,510 --> 00:31:08,300
and think about
who made the things you have?

733
00:31:08,310 --> 00:31:10,110
All the objects you possess,

734
00:31:10,160 --> 00:31:11,450
all of them,
without exception,

735
00:31:11,510 --> 00:31:13,260
have one substance in common.

736
00:31:13,270 --> 00:31:16,160
Do you know what this substance common
to all the things you have is? Labor

737
00:31:16,200 --> 00:31:19,060
Labor, folks, is
a social substance.

738
00:31:19,060 --> 00:31:23,760
Every commodity has in it
some amount of crystallized labor.

739
00:31:23,760 --> 00:31:26,140
Is Value the same thing as price?
No, no.

740
00:31:26,140 --> 00:31:27,670
Is price Value, chat?
No.

741
00:31:27,720 --> 00:31:31,150
Every time you think you're not
understanding what Value is,

742
00:31:31,150 --> 00:31:34,640
be sure you're not
confusing it with price, OK?

743
00:31:34,650 --> 00:31:35,090
So,

744
00:31:35,090 --> 00:31:37,160
what determines the Value of
a commodity?

745
00:31:37,160 --> 00:31:41,890
The labor is socially necessary
for the production of this commodity.

746
00:31:41,910 --> 00:31:44,870
Folks, what has more Value,
a glass or a car? A car.

747
00:31:45,020 --> 00:31:45,510
Why?

748
00:31:45,530 --> 00:31:50,370
Why? Because the amount of labor
needed to make a car is way bigger.

749
00:31:50,370 --> 00:31:52,590
Making a car requires way more labor
than making a glass.

750
00:31:52,660 --> 00:31:55,480
Therefore, a car has
much more Value than glass.

751
00:31:55,530 --> 00:31:57,980
Does this mean that if I had a glass factory,

752
00:31:57,980 --> 00:32:01,060
and it took me the same amount of time
needed to make a car, to make this glass,

753
00:32:01,090 --> 00:32:04,190
the glass would get more expensive?
No, OK?

754
00:32:04,250 --> 00:32:05,590
No.
For the love of God, no.

755
00:32:05,590 --> 00:32:12,050
Value is determined by the amount of
socially necessary labor.

756
00:32:12,050 --> 00:32:13,880
The social criteria are fundamental.

757
00:32:13,920 --> 00:32:16,820
What determines Value is the amount of labor

758
00:32:16,820 --> 00:32:19,090
in a certain social state

759
00:32:19,130 --> 00:32:21,610
and under
specific productive conditions

760
00:32:21,620 --> 00:32:23,440
of an entire society.

761
00:32:23,470 --> 00:32:27,800
It's how much labor is required
to produce a glass in the entire society,

762
00:32:27,880 --> 00:32:31,370
and not how much you, an individual,
needs to produce a glass, OK?

763
00:32:31,400 --> 00:32:34,120
So, if Value is not price,
what is price, then?

764
00:32:34,120 --> 00:32:37,040
Price is
the expression of value as money

765
00:32:37,190 --> 00:32:38,420
an expression in money.

766
00:32:38,440 --> 00:32:41,810
Price usually
gravitates around value.

767
00:32:41,830 --> 00:32:43,710
This price
gravitates around Value,

768
00:32:43,730 --> 00:32:44,770
Adam Smith,

769
00:32:44,810 --> 00:32:46,170
Adam Smith,
not Marx,

770
00:32:46,210 --> 00:32:48,080
called it central price.

771
00:32:48,120 --> 00:32:50,820
Once a commodity is produced by labor

772
00:32:50,820 --> 00:32:52,970
and it goes out
to be sold on the market.

773
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:56,300
It (the commodity) will get
closer to its value.

774
00:32:56,300 --> 00:33:00,880
Value is not price,
value is a property of the commodity,

775
00:33:00,900 --> 00:33:05,110
and value is determined by
the amount of socially necessary labor.

776
00:33:05,110 --> 00:33:08,910
Remember we said that the commodity is
the center of all social relations?

777
00:33:08,910 --> 00:33:12,300
In Capitalism,
our labor power is also a commodity.

778
00:33:12,300 --> 00:33:15,050
We sell our labor power
at market price.

779
00:33:15,090 --> 00:33:17,050
If our labor power is
a commodity,

780
00:33:17,050 --> 00:33:19,370
and value is a property
of a commodity,

781
00:33:19,390 --> 00:33:20,970
What is the value of
our labor power?

782
00:33:20,970 --> 00:33:24,980
The value of our labor power is also
determined by the socially necessary labor,

783
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:26,120
but in another way,

784
00:33:26,120 --> 00:33:27,820
the value of
your labor power is

785
00:33:27,820 --> 00:33:31,940
determined by
all that reproduces you.

786
00:33:31,940 --> 00:33:34,710
It's the value of
everything you need to exist.

787
00:33:34,710 --> 00:33:38,040
Food, clothing,
roof, heating, etc.

788
00:33:38,070 --> 00:33:39,850
All that
you consume to exist

789
00:33:39,890 --> 00:33:42,390
has in it the socially necessary labor
needed to produce it.

790
00:33:42,410 --> 00:33:43,930
The Value of your labor power

791
00:33:43,970 --> 00:33:47,200
is the sum of the values of
all the things you need to exist.

792
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:48,660
And, in Capitalism,

793
00:33:48,690 --> 00:33:51,840
especially, with an extremely
unqualified workforce,

794
00:33:51,880 --> 00:33:56,570
the labor power's value gets close to
the bare minimum you need to maintain yourself

795
00:33:56,570 --> 00:34:00,140
So, when you sell your labor power
on the labor market,

796
00:34:00,170 --> 00:34:01,890
that's why we call it
the labor market,

797
00:34:01,970 --> 00:34:04,510
you are selling it
by its value,

798
00:34:04,520 --> 00:34:06,580
and the value of
your labor power is determined by

799
00:34:06,580 --> 00:34:09,520
what you need
to keep existing.

800
00:34:09,550 --> 00:34:11,540
And this you can derive
from reality, folks.

801
00:34:11,570 --> 00:34:15,940
Your salary is being paid to you so that
you can buy what you need to continue existing.

802
00:34:15,960 --> 00:34:17,280
Why is all of that so important?

803
00:34:17,280 --> 00:34:20,300
Because understanding
what value is makes us comprehend

804
00:34:20,760 --> 00:34:24,300
the greatest discovery of
Marxist Political Economy,

805
00:34:24,350 --> 00:34:25,370
which is Surplus Value.

806
00:34:25,430 --> 00:34:27,750
Without understanding value,
we would not understand the surplus value.

807
00:34:27,830 --> 00:34:29,930
Without understanding surplus,
we would not understand capitalism.

808
00:34:30,040 --> 00:34:33,030
"Surplus" can also be "surplus value".

809
00:34:33,030 --> 00:34:36,730
Got it? To understand surplus value,
we need to understand value.

810
00:34:36,730 --> 00:34:37,230
So:

811
00:34:37,230 --> 00:34:39,130
according to Engels,
the discovery of the surplus value is

812
00:34:39,160 --> 00:34:42,720
a discovery of the same magnitude
as Darwin's Theory of Evolution

813
00:34:42,800 --> 00:34:43,130
Why?

814
00:34:43,190 --> 00:34:48,430
Because it can expose, strip naked,
the internal mechanisms of exploitation.

815
00:34:48,540 --> 00:34:51,720
When we talk about
exploitation in Capitalism, folks,

816
00:34:51,830 --> 00:34:53,030
we are not judging it.

817
00:34:53,110 --> 00:34:56,200
We are describing
the mechanism of Capitalism.

818
00:34:56,240 --> 00:34:58,565
Talking about exploitation in Capitalism
isn't a judgment on moral grounds,

819
00:34:58,590 --> 00:35:00,220
it's merely descriptive.

820
00:35:00,220 --> 00:35:03,540
And this is only understood when
you understand what value and surplus value are.

821
00:35:03,550 --> 00:35:04,430
So, let's go over it again:

822
00:35:04,470 --> 00:35:06,330
what determines
the value of a commodity

823
00:35:06,370 --> 00:35:09,430
is the socially necessary labor contained
in this commodity.

824
00:35:09,550 --> 00:35:10,640
Who does this labor?

825
00:35:10,690 --> 00:35:11,920
It's the worker,
not the bourgeois.

826
00:35:11,920 --> 00:35:13,600
The bourgeois doesn't work,
who works is the worker.

827
00:35:13,610 --> 00:35:18,500
Very well, after working and creating this value,
in exchange, the worker earns a wage.

828
00:35:18,610 --> 00:35:23,300
But the wage of the worker is equal
to the value of his labor power,

829
00:35:23,380 --> 00:35:25,400
and not the value
they created while laboring!

830
00:35:25,480 --> 00:35:29,030
That means that while the worker is working,
and laboring, they create value, create value,

831
00:35:29,080 --> 00:35:33,230
but they earn the equivalent of the value of
the labor power in the form of a wage.

832
00:35:33,330 --> 00:35:36,330
That is, what they create has
no connection with what they earn.

833
00:35:36,470 --> 00:35:39,430
What they earn has a connection
with what they need to live.

834
00:35:39,430 --> 00:35:40,630
Imagine the following:

835
00:35:40,630 --> 00:35:43,630
If you have an 8-hour workday

836
00:35:43,640 --> 00:35:47,300
and in four hours you produce
the value equivalent to your salary,

837
00:35:47,370 --> 00:35:49,780
the other four hours
you worked for free.

838
00:35:49,850 --> 00:35:53,460
This free labor
we call surplus labor.

839
00:35:53,570 --> 00:35:56,090
The value created
in this surplus period is

840
00:35:56,110 --> 00:36:01,220
appropriated by the bourgeois
in the form of surplus value.

841
00:36:01,260 --> 00:36:05,430
Surplus value is the mechanism
by which the bourgeois profit.

842
00:36:05,550 --> 00:36:10,460
And we have three types of surplus value:
absolute, relative, and extraordinary.

843
00:36:10,530 --> 00:36:14,330
Absolute surplus value expands
as the labor hours expand.

844
00:36:14,390 --> 00:36:15,630
Remember what I said?

845
00:36:15,650 --> 00:36:19,370
You need 4 daily hours to generate the value of
your salary, and your workday has 8 hours.

846
00:36:19,420 --> 00:36:22,250
Out of a sudden, your workday goes up to 10 hours,
without a wage increase.

847
00:36:22,280 --> 00:36:23,500
You've created
more surplus value.

848
00:36:23,560 --> 00:36:27,230
Absolute surplus value: the workday increases,
so the capitalist's profit increases.

849
00:36:27,340 --> 00:36:30,400
Now, relative surplus value is:
imagine that you work 8 hours a day,

850
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:32,160
but the factory got optimized.

851
00:36:32,160 --> 00:36:36,930
Instead of producing x chairs,
you produce, in the same amount of time, 2x chairs.

852
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:38,120
But you earn the same salary.

853
00:36:38,150 --> 00:36:40,600
You relatively increase the extraction of value;

854
00:36:40,600 --> 00:36:42,760
the labor time needed is the same,
but you can produce way more.

855
00:36:42,760 --> 00:36:47,030
And the extraordinary surplus value has to do
with the production of the same objects,

856
00:36:47,030 --> 00:36:49,770
of the same commodities,
but in other companies.

857
00:36:49,870 --> 00:36:50,390
For example:

858
00:36:50,390 --> 00:36:52,280
if there are many companies
producing chairs,

859
00:36:52,280 --> 00:36:54,850
and one of them discovers
a much faster way to produce,

860
00:36:54,890 --> 00:36:56,900
when this commodity
goes to the market,

861
00:36:56,940 --> 00:37:01,440
it, being sold at a similar price as the others,
will yield more profit.

862
00:37:01,440 --> 00:37:05,870
So, extraordinary surplus value
is relative to the industry as a whole,

863
00:37:05,870 --> 00:37:08,910
when some company discovers
a way to lower their costs.

864
00:37:08,910 --> 00:37:11,540
This surplus value tends
to find an equilibrium in two ways:

865
00:37:11,800 --> 00:37:13,900
either when some other companies
also gets optimized,

866
00:37:13,900 --> 00:37:16,100
or when all the others go bankrupt,
creating a monopoly.

867
00:37:16,130 --> 00:37:20,570
The point is: the final goal of every bourgeois is
the increase in surplus value.

868
00:37:20,570 --> 00:37:22,210
The increase.
The increase.

869
00:37:22,210 --> 00:37:23,670
This is not moral judgment.

870
00:37:23,670 --> 00:37:27,340
Marx at no moment makes
some moral judgment.

871
00:37:27,340 --> 00:37:30,340
He doesn't say "it's bad", "good",
"ugly", "stupid", or "blockhead".

872
00:37:30,340 --> 00:37:37,440
Saying that the goal of the bourgeois is
the increase of surplus value is descriptive,

873
00:37:37,440 --> 00:37:41,710
because this is observable,
we can verify it in reality.

874
00:37:41,790 --> 00:37:43,060
And what is important here?

875
00:37:43,100 --> 00:37:45,420
As profit is extracted
utilizing the surplus value,

876
00:37:45,470 --> 00:37:49,640
the bourgeois incorporates
this profit back into their capital.

877
00:37:49,660 --> 00:37:51,060
When the surplus value is extracted,

878
00:37:51,110 --> 00:37:55,140
the bourgeois reinvests it in production
to increase the extraction of surplus value.

879
00:37:55,230 --> 00:37:57,730
They refine more
this extraction each time more

880
00:37:57,730 --> 00:38:00,660
in an endless
and unceasing cycle.

881
00:38:00,690 --> 00:38:04,840
Capitalism has shown
a cyclical crises since its beginnings.

882
00:38:04,940 --> 00:38:09,660
Already in the 1870's,
Engels talked about seven crises of capitalism.

883
00:38:09,870 --> 00:38:11,920
Seven!
In the 19th century.

884
00:38:11,960 --> 00:38:14,210
This is when capitalism was
way smaller than it is today;

885
00:38:14,310 --> 00:38:15,990
when it was restricted to
just a few of countries.

886
00:38:16,040 --> 00:38:17,180
So, let's wrap it up?

887
00:38:17,220 --> 00:38:20,220
Marx's critique of Political Economy
focuses on analyzing capitalism.

888
00:38:20,300 --> 00:38:23,540
Capitalism is a mode of production based
on the employment of big industries.

889
00:38:23,540 --> 00:38:27,140
in the division of labor,
in class society, in private property,

890
00:38:27,340 --> 00:38:30,910
in the commodity as center of social relations
and constant expansion of capital.

891
00:38:31,020 --> 00:38:32,450
Let's recap some concepts.

892
00:38:32,480 --> 00:38:34,290
We have seen the value
and surplus value.

893
00:38:34,320 --> 00:38:36,170
Value:
it is a "property of the commodity.”

894
00:38:36,210 --> 00:38:39,170
And this property
is "determined by the socially necessary labor.”

895
00:38:39,260 --> 00:38:44,420
Surplus value is the "value created by the worker
which is appropriated by the bourgeois",

896
00:38:44,450 --> 00:38:45,840
and that doesn't return to the worker.

897
00:38:45,880 --> 00:38:46,800
This surplus value can be:

898
00:38:46,800 --> 00:38:49,560
"absolute",
when the working hours increase;

899
00:38:49,580 --> 00:38:51,170
"relative",
when productivity increases;

900
00:38:51,170 --> 00:38:54,920
"extraordinary" when the productivity
in comparison to other factories increases.

901
00:38:55,260 --> 00:38:55,570
OK?

902
00:38:55,570 --> 00:38:56,870
And why is it all that important

903
00:38:56,910 --> 00:38:58,290
Weren't we going to
talk about communism?

904
00:38:58,320 --> 00:38:59,700
Why are we talking
so much about capitalism?

905
00:38:59,750 --> 00:39:02,450
Understanding the capitalist
mode of production is necessary

906
00:39:02,460 --> 00:39:05,940
so we can walk towards
some other mode of production,

907
00:39:06,020 --> 00:39:09,330
and transform our productive forces
and our relations of production.

908
00:39:09,360 --> 00:39:13,910
Remember we said that Marxism and Communism
have an aversion towards utopianism?

909
00:39:13,970 --> 00:39:15,270
Towards utopia, idealism?

910
00:39:15,320 --> 00:39:20,440
Every Marxist analysis,
starts from material reality.

911
00:39:20,550 --> 00:39:23,170
This is Marx's object of study:

912
00:39:23,210 --> 00:39:29,200
observing capitalism's reality,
the reality in which he was living.

913
00:39:29,240 --> 00:39:29,720
OK?

914
00:39:29,740 --> 00:39:33,000
And then,
we go to the last pillar of Marxism,

915
00:39:33,020 --> 00:39:36,810
which we call
scientific socialism.

916
00:39:36,890 --> 00:39:39,450
So, by now we've got a basic,
and I mean really basic, analysis

917
00:39:39,490 --> 00:39:41,160
of the way capitalism works,
then what?

918
00:39:41,200 --> 00:39:43,810
We've seen that capitalism exploits us
and throws us into poverty.

919
00:39:43,910 --> 00:39:44,510
So, what to do?

920
00:39:44,540 --> 00:39:44,840
Very well,

921
00:39:44,860 --> 00:39:48,240
capitalism has developed
our productive forces in a way never seen before.

922
00:39:48,290 --> 00:39:52,910
It brought an unprecedented level
of productivity, unknown to humanity by then.

923
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:56,710
However, at the same time, it threw
a huge part of humanity into misery,

924
00:39:56,770 --> 00:39:58,160
excluded from society

925
00:39:58,220 --> 00:40:01,790
A huge chunk of people was proletarianized,
lost everything they had,

926
00:40:01,840 --> 00:40:05,300
and turned to sell their work force
in exchange for the bare minimum to survive

927
00:40:05,330 --> 00:40:07,630
while bearing
strenuous work hours.

928
00:40:07,660 --> 00:40:08,040
So,

929
00:40:08,060 --> 00:40:11,220
how did we sharply increase
productivity and poverty at the same time?

930
00:40:11,260 --> 00:40:12,350
How did we increase

931
00:40:12,390 --> 00:40:16,000
machinery and automation levels
and work load simultaneously?

932
00:40:16,030 --> 00:40:19,020
Why is it that there's more and more automation
and work load never decreases?

933
00:40:19,040 --> 00:40:22,770
Those are the contradictions
that will be our aim in this next analysis.

934
00:40:22,880 --> 00:40:23,290
Okay, next:

935
00:40:23,310 --> 00:40:24,620
"Analyzing Capitalism",

936
00:40:24,650 --> 00:40:28,610
We've concluded
that capitalism is based on exploitation, right?

937
00:40:28,640 --> 00:40:28,950
Very well,

938
00:40:28,980 --> 00:40:30,580
The first thing
we can know for a fact is:

939
00:40:30,630 --> 00:40:34,750
there's no exploiters without the exploited,
this has always been the case, right?

940
00:40:34,780 --> 00:40:36,990
Were there always
exploiters and the exploited?

941
00:40:37,040 --> 00:40:38,120
Let's dig into that.

942
00:40:38,180 --> 00:40:39,090
We know also

943
00:40:39,100 --> 00:40:42,460
that the mechanism of exploitation comes
through private property.

944
00:40:42,490 --> 00:40:45,740
Marx, through the method
(dialectical and historical materialism),

945
00:40:45,820 --> 00:40:48,110
come to the reasoning that
there has not always been private property.

946
00:40:48,150 --> 00:40:49,760
And not just that,

947
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:52,960
he also found that there's been different kinds
of private property throughout history.

948
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:56,750
The same goes to social classes,
those weren't always in the scene,

949
00:40:56,800 --> 00:41:00,400
throughout history,
social classes are quite a lot different.

950
00:41:03,090 --> 00:41:05,480
It's that the existence of social classes
and private property

951
00:41:05,510 --> 00:41:09,730
Is linked to a certain phase of
the development of production.

952
00:41:09,760 --> 00:41:10,970
What's so relevant about that?

953
00:41:11,020 --> 00:41:15,470
This conclusion by Marx
makes us be able to see that

954
00:41:15,500 --> 00:41:18,740
These social organizations,
these human organizations,

955
00:41:18,810 --> 00:41:21,330
are not indispensable.

956
00:41:21,350 --> 00:41:24,660
Private property isn't indispensable
for human society.

957
00:41:24,700 --> 00:41:27,310
Social classes aren't imperative
for human society.

958
00:41:27,320 --> 00:41:31,880
So, the notion that there will always be
employers and employees is false.

959
00:41:31,930 --> 00:41:34,990
Not only this,
through the material analysis of capitalism,

960
00:41:35,010 --> 00:41:36,870
Marx got to the conclusion

961
00:41:36,900 --> 00:41:42,390
that we already have resources
to march towards another society,

962
00:41:42,390 --> 00:41:44,470
With different social relations.

963
00:41:44,500 --> 00:41:45,030
So, let's go,

964
00:41:45,060 --> 00:41:46,870
a little quote from Marx here
for us to discuss,

965
00:41:46,900 --> 00:41:48,210
from the Communist Manifesto:

966
00:41:48,210 --> 00:41:52,940
"an epidemic that, in all earlier epochs,
would have seemed an absurdity

967
00:41:53,010 --> 00:41:54,520
— the epidemic of over-production.

968
00:41:54,520 --> 00:41:59,880
The conditions of bourgeois society are too
narrow to comprise the wealth created by them"

969
00:41:59,880 --> 00:42:01,130
What does Marx mean here?

970
00:42:01,130 --> 00:42:02,290
By the first time in history,

971
00:42:02,290 --> 00:42:06,850
human society was dealing
with the inverse of its usual problem.

972
00:42:06,850 --> 00:42:09,850
Until then, society had only dealt
with the issue of lacking production.

973
00:42:09,850 --> 00:42:12,190
Society had a scarcity issue.

974
00:42:12,190 --> 00:42:16,260
The capitalist mode of production
brought a new problem:

975
00:42:16,330 --> 00:42:17,430
excess of production.

976
00:42:17,460 --> 00:42:18,080
The catch is:

977
00:42:18,080 --> 00:42:20,650
there's only excess
of production in capitalism,

978
00:42:20,650 --> 00:42:27,140
for the capitalist means of production
are illogic, irrational.

979
00:42:27,160 --> 00:42:30,750
Capitalism does not produce
to satisfy our needs,

980
00:42:30,830 --> 00:42:32,930
it does to sate
the needs of the capital.

981
00:42:32,930 --> 00:42:36,870
If production doesn't become capital
it is disposed of.

982
00:42:36,900 --> 00:42:37,720
Meaning,

983
00:42:37,780 --> 00:42:41,770
the capitalist means of production
jeopardize our production capability.

984
00:42:41,770 --> 00:42:46,830
We're hindered from producing
more and better due to capitalism.

985
00:42:46,830 --> 00:42:52,490
So according to Marx,
the capitalist ways are obsolete.

986
00:42:52,530 --> 00:42:53,960
OBSOLETE.

987
00:42:53,960 --> 00:42:56,930
They need to be transformed.

988
00:42:56,930 --> 00:42:59,450
Is such transformation possible?
Not only possible.

989
00:42:59,450 --> 00:43:01,850
according to Marx,
it's very likely.

990
00:43:01,890 --> 00:43:02,220
Why?

991
00:43:02,220 --> 00:43:03,780
Throughout capitalism's development,

992
00:43:03,780 --> 00:43:08,860
it creates its own contradictions
which will bring its downfall,

993
00:43:08,860 --> 00:43:09,720
unavoidably

994
00:43:09,720 --> 00:43:13,070
By expanding,
capitalism generate proletarians,

995
00:43:13,100 --> 00:43:16,580
proletarian by proletarian,
more, more and more

996
00:43:16,580 --> 00:43:20,370
This class that it creates is
the one that antagonizes it.

997
00:43:20,370 --> 00:43:24,910
Marxism's greatest asset was to perceive
that there are not only classes,

998
00:43:24,910 --> 00:43:29,420
and that those classes are
unavoidably antagonistic to each other.

999
00:43:29,420 --> 00:43:34,280
They'll never reach harmony,
for they have contradictory interests.

1000
00:43:34,280 --> 00:43:38,730
To this antagonism between
the two main classes of capitalist society,

1001
00:43:38,730 --> 00:43:43,340
we call class struggle.
Class struggle.

1002
00:43:43,340 --> 00:43:45,680
For Marxism,

1003
00:43:45,680 --> 00:43:47,680
every doctrine,

1004
00:43:47,680 --> 00:43:49,900
each and every set of principles

1005
00:43:49,920 --> 00:43:53,990
that attempts to balance classes,
and harmonize classes

1006
00:43:53,990 --> 00:43:57,600
are utopian.
It's fallacious.

1007
00:43:57,600 --> 00:43:58,660
It's a facade.

1008
00:43:58,660 --> 00:44:03,450
If there is an exploited class,
there will be an exploiter class above it

1009
00:44:03,450 --> 00:44:04,150
Every time.

1010
00:44:04,150 --> 00:44:05,990
The Utopians,
which we talked about before,

1011
00:44:05,990 --> 00:44:07,900
had no perspective
of any class.

1012
00:44:07,900 --> 00:44:11,810
They sought a society
that balanced all of humanity.

1013
00:44:11,810 --> 00:44:16,340
having the perspective of the classes is
knowing that they are antagonistic.

1014
00:44:16,380 --> 00:44:20,530
it is fundamental
to what we call Scientific Socialism;

1015
00:44:20,530 --> 00:44:21,740
which is how Engels name it.

1016
00:44:21,740 --> 00:44:25,900
This expression appeared
to contrast with Utopian Socialism.

1017
00:44:25,900 --> 00:44:27,240
So, why does this matter?

1018
00:44:27,240 --> 00:44:28,350
According to Marx,

1019
00:44:28,350 --> 00:44:31,110
the class struggle
between the bourgeoisie and the proletariat

1020
00:44:31,110 --> 00:44:34,070
will lead
to a rupture with capitalism.

1021
00:44:34,070 --> 00:44:37,120
What's relevant about Marx is
that not only does he identify the classes,

1022
00:44:37,150 --> 00:44:41,300
But he also credits the revolutionary protagonist
to the exploited class.

1023
00:44:41,300 --> 00:44:43,910
The proletariat becomes
the revolution's Subject.

1024
00:44:43,910 --> 00:44:47,650
The proletariat belongs
to the class that will conduct revolution,

1025
00:44:47,650 --> 00:44:48,810
unlike the Utopians.

1026
00:44:48,810 --> 00:44:49,850
Utopians believed

1027
00:44:49,850 --> 00:44:53,730
that the working-class were
unable to lead any change.

1028
00:44:53,750 --> 00:44:55,840
That any change
would come top-down.

1029
00:44:55,840 --> 00:44:58,590
Marx said otherwise:
it will come bottom-up.

1030
00:44:58,590 --> 00:45:01,120
And how will this rupture
be conducted?

1031
00:45:01,160 --> 00:45:03,870
The proletarian class,
becoming aware of itself,

1032
00:45:03,870 --> 00:45:07,550
will organize
And seize the power of State

1033
00:45:07,580 --> 00:45:11,880
and institute something called
the dictatorship of the proletariat.

1034
00:45:11,880 --> 00:45:14,050
What does dictatorship
of the proletariat mean?

1035
00:45:14,050 --> 00:45:17,680
To Marx, we live in a dictatorship
of the bourgeoisie.

1036
00:45:17,680 --> 00:45:22,110
The State does not arise as
an apparatus that balances society.

1037
00:45:22,110 --> 00:45:24,270
You'll see idealists,
to this day,

1038
00:45:24,270 --> 00:45:28,630
saying that the State arises
to reduce society's conflicts.

1039
00:45:28,630 --> 00:45:29,240
No.

1040
00:45:29,240 --> 00:45:34,480
For Marx, the State is
an apparatus of specific class violence.

1041
00:45:34,480 --> 00:45:40,750
The State arises so the ruling class maintain
the ruled one in its due place,

1042
00:45:40,750 --> 00:45:42,710
through violence.

1043
00:45:42,710 --> 00:45:44,420
In the capitalist society,

1044
00:45:44,420 --> 00:45:48,360
who has the State apparatus
is the bourgeoisie.

1045
00:45:48,360 --> 00:45:51,760
The State is puppeteered
by the bourgeoisie

1046
00:45:51,760 --> 00:45:54,800
to maintain the bourgeoisie on power.
Alright?

1047
00:45:54,820 --> 00:46:00,010
So, for Marx, we live in something called
the dictatorship of the bourgeoisie.

1048
00:46:00,040 --> 00:46:02,080
If there is capitalism,
there's dictatorship of the bourgeoisie.

1049
00:46:02,080 --> 00:46:03,770
Well, if the State is necessarily

1050
00:46:03,770 --> 00:46:06,760
an apparatus of
specific class violence,

1051
00:46:06,760 --> 00:46:08,970
when the working-class
takes the State,

1052
00:46:08,970 --> 00:46:11,300
won't it still be that?
Yes, exactly.

1053
00:46:11,300 --> 00:46:12,670
But this pyramid
will be turned.

1054
00:46:12,670 --> 00:46:15,630
The State is an apparatus of
specific class violence;

1055
00:46:15,630 --> 00:46:17,960
with the working-class taking
the State apparatus,

1056
00:46:17,960 --> 00:46:22,150
it will use the State apparatus for,
through violence,

1057
00:46:22,150 --> 00:46:24,090
eradicate the bourgeoisie as class.

1058
00:46:24,090 --> 00:46:26,960
The State is an apparatus
of specific class violence,

1059
00:46:26,960 --> 00:46:28,960
and it will still keep being as such.

1060
00:46:28,960 --> 00:46:30,960
So, the State
in the hands of the working class

1061
00:46:30,960 --> 00:46:34,950
will oppress the bourgeoisie
until it vanishes,

1062
00:46:34,990 --> 00:46:37,830
and while
the other classes vanishes,

1063
00:46:37,870 --> 00:46:40,370
the State becomes obsolete.

1064
00:46:40,370 --> 00:46:42,260
Once there are no more classes
to oppress,

1065
00:46:42,260 --> 00:46:44,440
the State no longer needs to exist,

1066
00:46:44,440 --> 00:46:47,990
and it languishes.
It disappears.

1067
00:46:47,990 --> 00:46:50,110
It becomes useless.

1068
00:46:50,140 --> 00:46:54,160
That's Marx's vision of the transition
from socialism to communism.

1069
00:46:54,200 --> 00:46:58,050
That's the way the State dies out
in the Marxist point of view.

1070
00:46:58,100 --> 00:46:59,440
Alright?
So, let's recapitulate.

1071
00:46:59,440 --> 00:47:03,110
"The scientific socialism: demonstrates
that the existence of classes

1072
00:47:03,150 --> 00:47:05,990
it's connected only to certain phases
of production development.”

1073
00:47:06,020 --> 00:47:08,840
Once, they did not exist.
They can cease to exist.

1074
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:10,160
With the private property,
it's the same thing.

1075
00:47:10,190 --> 00:47:13,960
"The class struggle conduces,
necessarily, to proletariat's dictatorship",

1076
00:47:13,960 --> 00:47:15,930
and "this dictatorship is nothing more

1077
00:47:15,930 --> 00:47:20,820
than the transition to abolition of
all classes, and to a classless society."

1078
00:47:20,850 --> 00:47:22,660
That's Marx's great discovery.

1079
00:47:22,660 --> 00:47:26,120
And here, we have to make
a small observation:

1080
00:47:26,140 --> 00:47:28,170
I've been using the terms
socialism and communism,

1081
00:47:28,200 --> 00:47:30,140
but we need to distinguish
one from the other.

1082
00:47:30,140 --> 00:47:32,110
So, firstly:
socialism and communism

1083
00:47:32,110 --> 00:47:35,080
only have the meaning they have today
after the Russian Revolution.

1084
00:47:35,110 --> 00:47:35,370
So,

1085
00:47:35,370 --> 00:47:39,240
Socialism is
the step of the transition to communism.

1086
00:47:39,410 --> 00:47:42,530
During socialism,
the working class will be at power

1087
00:47:42,560 --> 00:47:45,280
and it will oppress the bourgeoisie
until the classes vanish.

1088
00:47:45,380 --> 00:47:47,780
During communism,
the classes no longer exist.

1089
00:47:47,810 --> 00:47:49,280
Marx doesn't use these terms.

1090
00:47:49,320 --> 00:47:52,900
Marx uses
"the first stage of communist society"

1091
00:47:52,950 --> 00:47:54,980
and "superior stage
of communist society".

1092
00:47:55,010 --> 00:47:58,340
The reason behind it, after
the Russian Revolution, the terms are switched,

1093
00:47:58,340 --> 00:48:00,080
it's historical,
and it has the reason to be so.

1094
00:48:00,200 --> 00:48:02,080
It made sense
at the time it came about.

1095
00:48:02,100 --> 00:48:05,020
But do know that, from now on,
I will use "socialism" as transition

1096
00:48:05,050 --> 00:48:06,280
and "communism" as destination.

1097
00:48:06,340 --> 00:48:11,860
Another thing: Marx doesn't determine
the specific characteristics of socialism.

1098
00:48:11,880 --> 00:48:13,760
Marx was a materialist.

1099
00:48:13,800 --> 00:48:18,180
For him, any prediction
or recipe was idealism.

1100
00:48:18,210 --> 00:48:23,940
All societies should start
from a material analysis. A real one, OK? Not ideal.

1101
00:48:23,940 --> 00:48:26,600
Marx can't make the same mistake
he criticized in the Utopians.

1102
00:48:26,600 --> 00:48:28,340
So, Marx only presents
general ideas:

1103
00:48:28,340 --> 00:48:31,600
socialism is the working-class at power,
dictatorship of the proletariat

1104
00:48:31,600 --> 00:48:33,450
and transition in direction of
a society without classes.

1105
00:48:33,460 --> 00:48:35,040
That's why every time someone asks

1106
00:48:35,060 --> 00:48:37,310
"how many brands of washing powder
will exist in socialism?",

1107
00:48:37,310 --> 00:48:40,020
anything we could answer
is going to be speculation.

1108
00:48:40,040 --> 00:48:42,930
There's no way to know.
We'll know the details

1109
00:48:43,040 --> 00:48:44,360
from experience.

1110
00:48:44,360 --> 00:48:47,820
And the soviets detail
much more about what is socialism. Why?

1111
00:48:47,820 --> 00:48:49,400
Because they had a socialist experience!

1112
00:48:49,470 --> 00:48:53,460
Marx didn't.
Therefore, he didn't dare to predict the future

1113
00:48:53,520 --> 00:48:55,460
beyond what he knew was possible.

1114
00:48:55,460 --> 00:48:58,880
He knew it was possible
that the working-class take the State apparatus;

1115
00:48:58,880 --> 00:49:02,600
That it was possible for the workers to use
the State apparatus to oppress the bourgeoisie;

1116
00:49:02,600 --> 00:49:03,460
He knew it was possible.

1117
00:49:03,460 --> 00:49:04,900
And it was possible.
And it was done!

1118
00:49:04,900 --> 00:49:07,180
All of this came from
the material analysis.

1119
00:49:07,180 --> 00:49:08,280
Another thing:

1120
00:49:08,280 --> 00:49:12,780
that means that, after the revolution,
on day one of socialism,

1121
00:49:12,780 --> 00:49:14,640
all the contradictions will go away?

1122
00:49:14,640 --> 00:49:16,400
Contradiction's gone.

1123
00:49:16,400 --> 00:49:20,020
The capitalism died,
any opposer died, and everything died. No.

1124
00:49:20,020 --> 00:49:21,100
Marx's quote:

1125
00:49:21,100 --> 00:49:25,240
"What we have to deal with here i
s a communist society,

1126
00:49:25,240 --> 00:49:28,300
not as it has developed
on its own foundations,

1127
00:49:28,390 --> 00:49:32,320
but, on the contrary,
just as it emerges from capitalist society;

1128
00:49:32,320 --> 00:49:34,520
[a communist society],
which is thus

1129
00:49:34,610 --> 00:49:38,020
in every respect,
economically, morally, and intellectually,

1130
00:49:38,020 --> 00:49:42,920
still stamped with the birthmarks of
the old society from whose womb it emerges".

1131
00:49:42,920 --> 00:49:43,940
So, just remembering:

1132
00:49:43,950 --> 00:49:45,010
in this quote,

1133
00:49:45,060 --> 00:49:49,270
Marx is using the word communism
as we use the word socialism today, alright?

1134
00:49:49,290 --> 00:49:51,760
Here, Marx is talking about
the first stage of communism.

1135
00:49:51,760 --> 00:49:53,960
That's why I had
to clarify the vocabulary here.

1136
00:49:53,960 --> 00:49:54,870
What's the point here?

1137
00:49:54,920 --> 00:49:57,090
A society that comes
from the womb of another,

1138
00:49:57,120 --> 00:49:59,120
and with that it carries
its birthmarks.

1139
00:49:59,120 --> 00:50:04,100
If we have a capitalist, sexist society
and we go through a revolution,

1140
00:50:04,100 --> 00:50:07,300
the new society
will still be sexist.

1141
00:50:07,300 --> 00:50:09,200
This contradiction
will not disappear.

1142
00:50:09,200 --> 00:50:15,360
The question is, the new society gives us
the possibility to overcome sexism,

1143
00:50:15,360 --> 00:50:16,800
while capitalism doesn't.

1144
00:50:16,800 --> 00:50:20,700
Capitalism doesn't give us the opportunity
of overcoming many contradictions.

1145
00:50:20,700 --> 00:50:21,560
So,

1146
00:50:21,560 --> 00:50:25,360
Oh, but what about Cuba?
wasn't Cuba misogynist? wasn't Cuba homophobic?"

1147
00:50:25,360 --> 00:50:27,980
Cuba came from
a misogynist and homophobic society.

1148
00:50:27,980 --> 00:50:31,200
It would be strange if it wasn't so anymore
on day one of the revolution.

1149
00:50:31,200 --> 00:50:33,620
So, we can't
generalize socialism as well,

1150
00:50:33,620 --> 00:50:37,170
because each socialist experience will emerge
from a different capitalist experience;

1151
00:50:37,200 --> 00:50:40,580
with their own particularities and with
their particular contradictions. Alright?

1152
00:50:40,580 --> 00:50:42,920
That was all about Marxism.
We have:

1153
00:50:42,960 --> 00:50:45,800
dialectical and historical materialism,
political economy, and scientific socialism.

1154
00:50:45,800 --> 00:50:51,060
Now, we go to the last basic part
which is necessary and essential.

1155
00:50:51,060 --> 00:50:52,680
We're going to talk
about Lenin now.

1156
00:50:52,680 --> 00:50:54,900
This Lenin, here. So, let's go.
Why are we talking about Lenin?

1157
00:50:54,900 --> 00:50:56,210
By now, you should know

1158
00:50:56,270 --> 00:50:58,310
that the first successful revolution

1159
00:50:58,310 --> 00:51:01,010
of a socialist nature was
the Russian Revolution of 1917.

1160
00:51:01,040 --> 00:51:04,050
On the Russian Revolution,
and the whole Soviet experience,

1161
00:51:04,050 --> 00:51:06,050
I would need to do
a separate video.

1162
00:51:06,080 --> 00:51:08,320
Today we are going to talk about
the greatest leader of this revolution,

1163
00:51:08,370 --> 00:51:10,970
which is Vladimir Ilyich Ulianov,
or Lenin.

1164
00:51:10,990 --> 00:51:15,600
Because Lenin is the greatest Marxist
after Marx and Engels.

1165
00:51:15,600 --> 00:51:18,280
For those who don't know,
Lenin is a great theoretician.

1166
00:51:18,280 --> 00:51:20,980
And not only big,
but he is also unavoidable.

1167
00:51:20,980 --> 00:51:23,600
It was because
of Lenin's theoretical work

1168
00:51:23,600 --> 00:51:25,820
that the Russian Revolution was possible.

1169
00:51:25,820 --> 00:51:27,420
And why is Lenin so important?

1170
00:51:27,420 --> 00:51:31,760
Because Lenin gives
an operational dimension to Marxism,

1171
00:51:31,760 --> 00:51:36,580
he develops a method
for the practical application of Marxism.

1172
00:51:36,580 --> 00:51:40,640
And there are several elements
of what we call Leninism today,

1173
00:51:40,640 --> 00:51:43,820
but today I'm just going to talk about one,
which is perhaps the main one,

1174
00:51:43,820 --> 00:51:45,920
which is the party.

1175
00:51:45,920 --> 00:51:46,410
And come on,

1176
00:51:46,520 --> 00:51:48,300
let's talk about the party.

1177
00:51:48,300 --> 00:51:49,960
Since the time of Marx and Engels,

1178
00:51:49,960 --> 00:51:52,900
it was already known
that it was necessary to organize the class.

1179
00:51:52,900 --> 00:51:55,420
What did Lenin do?
He observed reality,

1180
00:51:55,420 --> 00:51:57,240
just like Marx and Engels did,

1181
00:51:57,240 --> 00:51:59,480
he saw how the class
was organized,

1182
00:51:59,480 --> 00:52:02,300
and proposed
a new form of organization.

1183
00:52:02,300 --> 00:52:06,340
This new form of organization
is called the Leninist party.

1184
00:52:06,340 --> 00:52:07,260
And then arises the question:

1185
00:52:07,260 --> 00:52:10,720
when we think of a party,
we think of abbreviations

1186
00:52:10,720 --> 00:52:12,840
that run for the parlament.

1187
00:52:12,840 --> 00:52:14,660
run for Congress, run for the Executive.

1188
00:52:14,660 --> 00:52:16,220
I'll tell you something
in advance:

1189
00:52:16,220 --> 00:52:17,660
that's not
what a Leninist party is about.

1190
00:52:17,660 --> 00:52:21,610
In fact, it has no intention
of winning the election, okay?

1191
00:52:21,630 --> 00:52:24,840
The Leninist party does
not come about to win elections.

1192
00:52:24,860 --> 00:52:26,390
What is the Leninist Party?

1193
00:52:26,460 --> 00:52:30,760
The Leninist party is
the organized detachment of the working-class.

1194
00:52:30,760 --> 00:52:32,110
Lenin used to say,
his quote:

1195
00:52:32,140 --> 00:52:38,300
“In its struggle for power the proletariat has
no other weapon but organization.”

1196
00:52:38,300 --> 00:52:41,860
The Leninist party,
unlike parties running for elections,

1197
00:52:41,860 --> 00:52:44,380
organizes itself
on a revolutionary basis.

1198
00:52:44,380 --> 00:52:48,940
The party's idea is to prepare
and mobilize the class to take power;

1199
00:52:48,940 --> 00:52:52,400
not in a peaceful way,
but in a combative way.

1200
00:52:52,400 --> 00:52:56,040
The seizure of power needs
to be done in a combative way,

1201
00:52:56,040 --> 00:52:59,360
because the ruling class
will not voluntarily relinquish power.

1202
00:52:59,360 --> 00:53:03,380
In Russia, that party
was the Bolshevik party.

1203
00:53:03,380 --> 00:53:05,380
What are the elements of this party?

1204
00:53:05,500 --> 00:53:11,480
Firstly, the party must be
the vanguard detachment of the class.

1205
00:53:11,480 --> 00:53:13,480
What does vanguard mean?

1206
00:53:13,480 --> 00:53:15,100
Vanguard is a military term.

1207
00:53:15,100 --> 00:53:18,960
Vanguard means who is in front,
it is the opposite of rearguard.

1208
00:53:18,960 --> 00:53:22,660
The vanguard is
the best elements of the working-class:

1209
00:53:22,660 --> 00:53:24,180
the most experienced,

1210
00:53:24,260 --> 00:53:27,580
most dedicated, most revolutionary,
most enlightened workers.

1211
00:53:27,630 --> 00:53:31,040
That party must arm itself
with a revolutionary theory;

1212
00:53:31,040 --> 00:53:32,520
Another quote from Lenin,
also famous:

1213
00:53:32,520 --> 00:53:35,680
“Without revolutionary theory
there can be no revolutionary movement.”

1214
00:53:35,680 --> 00:53:36,510
But this party

1215
00:53:36,510 --> 00:53:39,990
cannot serve only to absorb
what the working class thinks.

1216
00:53:40,060 --> 00:53:44,000
The party appears, and then the idea
is not to see what the working class is thinking

1217
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:47,420
and represent the class
from what it is spontaneously thinking.

1218
00:53:47,420 --> 00:53:50,960
The party has to arm the class
with revolutionary theory;

1219
00:53:50,960 --> 00:53:54,720
because, for Lenin, the working class
organizes spontaneously.

1220
00:53:54,720 --> 00:53:57,720
But this working-class organization
is limited.

1221
00:53:57,720 --> 00:53:59,840
The class,
when organized spontaneously,

1222
00:53:59,860 --> 00:54:02,860
usually fights for the improvement
of their immediate condition

1223
00:54:02,860 --> 00:54:05,980
— salary improvement,
reduced working hours, labor rights —

1224
00:54:05,980 --> 00:54:09,020
but it does not fight towards
overthrowing the system.

1225
00:54:09,020 --> 00:54:12,440
Why it is so?
Because it cannot see
the mechanism of this system.

1226
00:54:12,490 --> 00:54:15,960
Since capitalism is a system,
it is a synthesis, it is an abstraction,

1227
00:54:15,960 --> 00:54:18,540
you cannot approach the worker,
point and say “capitalism is there”.

1228
00:54:18,540 --> 00:54:20,640
But they can see
that they can't pay the bills,

1229
00:54:20,640 --> 00:54:22,320
they can see
that they are working too hard,

1230
00:54:22,320 --> 00:54:24,320
and they can see that
when they get sick they get screwed.

1231
00:54:24,320 --> 00:54:25,380
They can see all of this.

1232
00:54:25,380 --> 00:54:27,000
And then the class
will organize itself.

1233
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:29,720
But the party cannot
just absorb this demand.

1234
00:54:29,720 --> 00:54:31,760
It has to arm the class
with something else.

1235
00:54:31,880 --> 00:54:33,700
And that something else
is the overthrow of the system!

1236
00:54:33,700 --> 00:54:37,300
That's why this party needs
to be leading the class.

1237
00:54:37,380 --> 00:54:40,130
And mind you,
it's not above!

1238
00:54:40,160 --> 00:54:41,460
It's not above.

1239
00:54:41,460 --> 00:54:44,380
It's ahead! It's ahead.

1240
00:54:44,480 --> 00:54:47,640
The party has to be
the political leader of the class. Why?

1241
00:54:47,640 --> 00:54:52,220
Because it can arm the class
with revolutionary tactical theory.

1242
00:54:52,220 --> 00:54:56,780
But this party can never
disconnect from the masses.

1243
00:54:56,780 --> 00:54:59,020
It has to have the advanced
detachments of the class,

1244
00:54:59,020 --> 00:55:00,940
but not isolate himself from the class.

1245
00:55:00,940 --> 00:55:03,080
It has to be connected
to the masses

1246
00:55:03,080 --> 00:55:06,360
and has to convince
the masses.

1247
00:55:06,380 --> 00:55:10,580
The party needs to work closely
with the entire working class

1248
00:55:10,620 --> 00:55:13,820
to gain moral credit
and political credit

1249
00:55:13,820 --> 00:55:17,220
through example,
through persuasion.

1250
00:55:17,220 --> 00:55:20,500
And for that, it needs to be organized.
What does that mean?

1251
00:55:20,560 --> 00:55:25,420
Within a Leninist party,
discipline must be ironclad

1252
00:55:25,420 --> 00:55:26,480
but willing.

1253
00:55:26,480 --> 00:55:27,880
When you join the party,

1254
00:55:27,880 --> 00:55:32,360
you willingly submit
to iron discipline.

1255
00:55:32,360 --> 00:55:36,220
And this is to awaken
the revolutionary spirit in the classes,

1256
00:55:36,220 --> 00:55:38,220
through example.

1257
00:55:38,220 --> 00:55:41,820
Does this mean that the party
should be the only organization?

1258
00:55:41,820 --> 00:55:44,520
It does not.
Should not. Cannot even.

1259
00:55:44,520 --> 00:55:47,440
Society must have
a series of class organizations:

1260
00:55:47,440 --> 00:55:51,540
Unions, cooperatives,
organizations, associations, and youths.

1261
00:55:51,540 --> 00:55:54,700
In the case of Russia,
there was a very important one: the soviets.

1262
00:55:54,700 --> 00:55:59,120
The soviets, folks, were the factory councils
that were formed spontaneously.

1263
00:55:59,120 --> 00:55:59,820
The point is:

1264
00:55:59,820 --> 00:56:03,440
the party cannot work in all areas
of the working class alone.

1265
00:56:03,480 --> 00:56:07,260
The party must work closely
with these organizations

1266
00:56:07,260 --> 00:56:11,120
to connect these organizations
in favor of the emancipatory struggle.

1267
00:56:11,120 --> 00:56:14,800
He must centralize
the tactics of these organizations.

1268
00:56:14,840 --> 00:56:17,020
How? Forcibly? No,

1269
00:56:17,020 --> 00:56:18,780
through persuasion.

1270
00:56:18,780 --> 00:56:21,500
Party members will join these organizations,

1271
00:56:21,500 --> 00:56:24,420
talk to the workers,
convince the workers,

1272
00:56:24,420 --> 00:56:27,720
demonstrate the need
to fight by example,

1273
00:56:27,750 --> 00:56:30,100
approach these organizations

1274
00:56:30,100 --> 00:56:33,560
and win the political support
of the masses.

1275
00:56:33,560 --> 00:56:37,580
The Bolshevik party did
exactly that.

1276
00:56:37,580 --> 00:56:40,720
The Bolshevik party did
not make a revolution

1277
00:56:40,720 --> 00:56:44,320
until it gained
a majority in the soviets.

1278
00:56:44,320 --> 00:56:47,460
The soviets were
the main organs of the working class;

1279
00:56:47,460 --> 00:56:49,900
the party worked
closely with the soviets

1280
00:56:49,900 --> 00:56:53,200
trying all the time to convince
the soviets of the need for a revolution,

1281
00:56:53,200 --> 00:56:55,100
It managed to convince the class,

1282
00:56:55,100 --> 00:56:56,580
won a majority in the soviets,

1283
00:56:56,580 --> 00:56:58,520
and then he led a revolution.

1284
00:56:58,530 --> 00:57:00,980
Lenin not only theorized,
but he also did!

1285
00:57:01,030 --> 00:57:02,780
He applied it!

1286
00:57:02,780 --> 00:57:04,520
Do you get how important this dude is?

1287
00:57:04,520 --> 00:57:06,920
So, the party has
two functions (in short, okay?)

1288
00:57:06,920 --> 00:57:08,480
Leading the class
into the revolution

1289
00:57:08,480 --> 00:57:10,980
and, after the revolution,
maintaining the revolution;

1290
00:57:10,980 --> 00:57:14,460
that is, it has a pre-revolution
and a post-revolution function.

1291
00:57:14,480 --> 00:57:17,040
Regardless of what you think
of everything I said;

1292
00:57:17,040 --> 00:57:19,040
“Oh Ian, I don't like it.
Not at all.

1293
00:57:19,040 --> 00:57:22,240
I found the party... bad.
I found it authoritative. Did not like it";

1294
00:57:22,270 --> 00:57:23,700
Regardless of
what you think,

1295
00:57:23,700 --> 00:57:28,330
Lenin's method is extremely efficient.

1296
00:57:28,380 --> 00:57:33,860
Ever heard of China? Cuba?
Korea? Vietnam? Albania? Burkina Faso?

1297
00:57:33,860 --> 00:57:35,780
Everyone, each one of them
used the Leninist method.

1298
00:57:35,780 --> 00:57:37,460
Regardless of
what you think,

1299
00:57:37,490 --> 00:57:42,680
Leninist party is an extremely
efficient method

1300
00:57:43,080 --> 00:57:45,820
for the seizure of power by the class.
Extremely efficient.

1301
00:57:45,820 --> 00:57:46,820
So, let's go.
Shall we review?

1302
00:57:46,820 --> 00:57:50,560
“Party." The Leninist party is:
the “organized detachment of the class”.

1303
00:57:50,560 --> 00:57:52,260
This detachment
must be a “vanguard”;

1304
00:57:52,260 --> 00:57:54,260
i.e. to be at the head of the class,
not above.

1305
00:57:54,290 --> 00:57:57,420
That party must be
“armed with theory”,

1306
00:57:57,420 --> 00:57:58,720
revolutionary theory.

1307
00:57:58,720 --> 00:58:01,560
This party has willing
and ironclad discipline.

1308
00:58:01,560 --> 00:58:03,900
That party “must mobilize
the class for the Revolution”,

1309
00:58:03,900 --> 00:58:05,980
and after the revolution
“it must maintain the revolution”.

1310
00:58:05,980 --> 00:58:07,060
That's the party.

1311
00:58:07,080 --> 00:58:11,800
There are many, many, other
Leninist elements about the organization

1312
00:58:11,800 --> 00:58:12,940
and other things.

1313
00:58:12,940 --> 00:58:13,600
The point is:

1314
00:58:13,600 --> 00:58:18,340
Lenin was a machine.
The guy wrote compulsively.

1315
00:58:18,340 --> 00:58:19,400
When he had a stroke,

1316
00:58:19,400 --> 00:58:22,190
the doctors had to ask for God's sake
for him to stop writing, for him not to die.

1317
00:58:22,240 --> 00:58:25,480
He was limited to writing ten minutes a day
so he wouldn't have another stroke.

1318
00:58:25,480 --> 00:58:27,280
Lenin is a Marxist machine.

1319
00:58:27,330 --> 00:58:29,940
In order to understand the organization,

1320
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:31,840
you have to read Lenin.
You really have to read it.

1321
00:58:31,840 --> 00:58:33,100
Let's head into the end, folks!

1322
00:58:33,100 --> 00:58:35,780
Remember I said I was going to give you
a reading guide for you to delve into?

1323
00:58:35,780 --> 00:58:37,040
So, let's get into
our reading guide,

1324
00:58:37,040 --> 00:58:38,060
and what I'm going to
talk about is this:

1325
00:58:38,060 --> 00:58:39,860
I'm going to suggest an order,

1326
00:58:39,880 --> 00:58:41,320
which is the one
that I'm going to present here.

1327
00:58:41,320 --> 00:58:43,420
All the books,
except the one on the screen,

1328
00:58:43,420 --> 00:58:46,120
will be available for free
in the video description.

1329
00:58:46,120 --> 00:58:46,540
So, let's go.

1330
00:58:46,540 --> 00:58:48,900
If you, after watching the video,
are still feeling insecure,

1331
00:58:48,900 --> 00:58:51,080
read this book by Grespan,
“Marx: an introduction”.

1332
00:58:51,080 --> 00:58:52,860
It's a super short book

1333
00:58:52,930 --> 00:58:55,780
that serves to introduce everyone
to the Marxist vocabulary,

1334
00:58:55,780 --> 00:58:59,240
and I recommend it even
to anyone who wants to learn to teach Marxism,

1335
00:58:59,240 --> 00:59:01,100
because it is a very didactic book.

1336
00:59:01,100 --> 00:59:03,300
There, the first text
I suggest after this video

1337
00:59:03,300 --> 00:59:05,540
is a very short text
by Lenin

1338
00:59:05,690 --> 00:59:09,400
called “The Three Sources
and Three Component Parts of Marxism”.

1339
00:59:09,400 --> 00:59:12,860
It's a text that Lenin wrote
on the 30th anniversary of Marx's death,

1340
00:59:12,860 --> 00:59:15,920
and Lenin talks about the Marxist sources

1341
00:59:15,920 --> 00:59:18,220
that have precisely
these three elements that we talked about:

1342
00:59:18,220 --> 00:59:19,860
philosophy, politics, and economics.

1343
00:59:19,860 --> 00:59:22,080
I highly recommend reading it,
it is a very small

1344
00:59:22,080 --> 00:59:23,640
and very enlightening text.

1345
00:59:23,720 --> 00:59:27,940
Remembering that Lenin did not have access
to all of Marx's texts, which we have access today.

1346
00:59:27,940 --> 00:59:30,440
So, there are texts that are missing,
simply because he did not have access to them.

1347
00:59:30,470 --> 00:59:32,320
Next. There are two together here,
look:

1348
00:59:32,380 --> 00:59:35,060
“Basic Principles of Communism”
by my boy Engels,

1349
00:59:35,060 --> 00:59:38,100
and “Manifesto of the Communist Party”
by homies Marx and Engels.

1350
00:59:38,140 --> 00:59:39,440
A little story for you:

1351
00:59:39,440 --> 00:59:43,380
Marx and Engels, in the 1840s,
joined something called the League of the Just.

1352
00:59:43,380 --> 00:59:46,980
What was the League of the Just? It was
an organization of emigrants from Germany,

1353
00:59:46,980 --> 00:59:49,220
which was a mixture
of German idealism and utopian socialism.

1354
00:59:49,220 --> 00:59:50,770
Marx and Engels enter the league

1355
00:59:50,790 --> 00:59:53,630
under the condition that they can change
the political line of the league.

1356
00:59:53,640 --> 00:59:57,300
So, they: change the name of the League of the Just
to the League of Communists;

1357
00:59:57,300 --> 01:00:01,780
change the motto from “all men are brothers”
to “workers of all countries, unite!”;

1358
01:00:01,780 --> 01:00:05,180
and are in charge of writing
the League's program.

1359
01:00:05,180 --> 01:00:07,840
At the first meeting of the League,
Engels goes, but Marx doesn't.

1360
01:00:07,870 --> 01:00:09,470
And then Engels is
in charge of writing

1361
01:00:09,470 --> 01:00:11,900
and he writes this book,
“Basic Principles of Communism”.

1362
01:00:11,920 --> 01:00:15,640
But he writes in the form of a catechism,
in questions and answers.

1363
01:00:15,640 --> 01:00:18,020
Marx doesn't like
the catechism format

1364
01:00:18,020 --> 01:00:20,240
and proposed the manifesto format.

1365
01:00:20,260 --> 01:00:23,440
And then they together write
“The Manifesto of the Communist Party”.

1366
01:00:23,470 --> 01:00:24,800
The first book by Engels,

1367
01:00:24,800 --> 01:00:26,840
Basic Principles of Communism,
was never published.

1368
01:00:26,870 --> 01:00:28,520
Not in life,
it was published later.

1369
01:00:28,550 --> 01:00:31,220
There are topics that Engels doesn't answer,
because it was a draft.

1370
01:00:31,240 --> 01:00:34,160
The Communist Manifesto
is a very important book,

1371
01:00:34,210 --> 01:00:37,260
because it is
the most well-finished first book on Marxism

1372
01:00:37,260 --> 01:00:39,060
with all its core elements.

1373
01:00:39,060 --> 01:00:40,680
It has three important things:

1374
01:00:40,680 --> 01:00:43,720
a historical analysis
as a starting point;

1375
01:00:43,720 --> 01:00:45,940
the perspective of classes as an axis;

1376
01:00:45,940 --> 01:00:48,940
and to place the proletarian class
as revolutionary,

1377
01:00:48,940 --> 01:00:50,480
a revolutionary subject.

1378
01:00:50,510 --> 01:00:52,080
The Communist Party Manifesto

1379
01:00:52,160 --> 01:00:54,600
is the most important
political document in history.

1380
01:00:54,640 --> 01:00:56,760
That document
changed the world.

1381
01:00:56,770 --> 01:00:58,760
Well worth reading and rereading
and reading again.

1382
01:00:58,760 --> 01:01:01,160
Moreover: in 1877,

1383
01:01:01,160 --> 01:01:03,160
Engels already old,
already elderly,

1384
01:01:03,160 --> 01:01:05,280
writes a book called
“Anti-Dühring”,

1385
01:01:05,280 --> 01:01:07,940
which is a critique of the philosophy
of a guy called Eugen Dühring.

1386
01:01:07,940 --> 01:01:09,840
Engels makes
such a concise critique,

1387
01:01:09,840 --> 01:01:12,740
and expounds Marxism
so competently,

1388
01:01:12,740 --> 01:01:14,740
that the book is somewhat
of an unexpected success.

1389
01:01:14,740 --> 01:01:17,440
And then he extracts
three chapters from Anti-Dühring,

1390
01:01:17,440 --> 01:01:18,680
which is a big book,

1391
01:01:18,710 --> 01:01:20,510
and publishes it
as this book here:

1392
01:01:20,560 --> 01:01:23,800
“From Utopian Socialism
to Scientific Socialism”

1393
01:01:23,870 --> 01:01:26,660
in which he talks about
some utopian thinkers

1394
01:01:26,690 --> 01:01:29,820
and contrasts with the thought
of historical and dialectical materialism.

1395
01:01:29,850 --> 01:01:32,800
This one is very interesting,
equally short,

1396
01:01:32,850 --> 01:01:34,060
and well worth reading.

1397
01:01:34,110 --> 01:01:36,180
One more:
“Value, Price and Profit”.

1398
01:01:36,230 --> 01:01:39,740
Value, Price and Profit
is a lecture given by Marx

1399
01:01:39,740 --> 01:01:44,260
in 1865 to the International
Workers' Association.

1400
01:01:44,260 --> 01:01:46,680
And in that book,
Marx is just talking about

1401
01:01:46,680 --> 01:01:50,980
how the wage is not related
to the price of the commodity.

1402
01:01:51,010 --> 01:01:54,380
And here, to explain this,
he explains value and surplus value.

1403
01:01:54,380 --> 01:01:56,980
So, I recommend it too.
It is a short text because it is a lecture;

1404
01:01:56,980 --> 01:02:00,320
and I recommend it as Marx's first text
on the critique of political economy.

1405
01:02:00,380 --> 01:02:03,040
But if you're feeling daring;

1406
01:02:03,070 --> 01:02:05,580
The critique of political economy,
Marx's magnanimous

1407
01:02:05,580 --> 01:02:07,820
"Capital".
Capital is three books,

1408
01:02:07,820 --> 01:02:10,290
three huge books, like that,
which took him 16 years to write.

1409
01:02:10,290 --> 01:02:11,120
It's worth reading.

1410
01:02:11,180 --> 01:02:15,120
But if you're not feeling so daring,
I'll recommend another book:

1411
01:02:15,160 --> 01:02:18,840
“Handbook of Political Economy”
by the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.

1412
01:02:18,840 --> 01:02:20,580
It's an equally gigantic book;

1413
01:02:20,580 --> 01:02:23,060
but it has,
due to the Soviet experience,

1414
01:02:23,060 --> 01:02:26,480
an excerpt that Capital does not have,
which is about the socialist mode of production.

1415
01:02:26,530 --> 01:02:29,820
So, if you have these doubts like:
“how is the organization of work under socialism?”

1416
01:02:29,820 --> 01:02:31,820
“How is surplus value in socialism?”,

1417
01:02:31,820 --> 01:02:33,700
“how is the factory in socialism?”,

1418
01:02:33,700 --> 01:02:35,500
“How is the mode of production?”, and such;

1419
01:02:35,580 --> 01:02:38,000
this book talks about it.
I recommend these two, okay?

1420
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:39,580
But they are gigantic books,

1421
01:02:39,580 --> 01:02:42,560
they are not books to leave by your bedside
and read every night, they are to be consulted.

1422
01:02:42,620 --> 01:02:45,000
One more:
“The German Ideology”.

1423
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:46,720
Lenin did not have access to this text.

1424
01:02:46,720 --> 01:02:51,060
This text is a text that
Marx and Engels wrote in 1846,

1425
01:02:51,060 --> 01:02:52,900
criticizing the Young Hegelians,

1426
01:02:52,920 --> 01:02:56,700
and it's the best example
we have of historical materialism.

1427
01:02:56,700 --> 01:02:57,860
Despite the book being gigantic,

1428
01:02:57,860 --> 01:03:00,310
I recommend only the first chapter,
the most important one,

1429
01:03:00,330 --> 01:03:01,660
which is “Feuerbach”.

1430
01:03:01,660 --> 01:03:04,700
That book was the one I read in college
to understand historical materialism.

1431
01:03:04,730 --> 01:03:08,100
It looks big, but in fact
only the first chapter is the most essential.

1432
01:03:08,140 --> 01:03:09,980
One more:
“Critique of the Gotha Program”.

1433
01:03:09,980 --> 01:03:11,220
“Oh, Ian,
I don't even know what Gotha is.

1434
01:03:11,220 --> 01:03:13,360
Why would I read this book
when I don't even know what Gotha is?"

1435
01:03:13,360 --> 01:03:14,480
The Gotha Program

1436
01:03:14,480 --> 01:03:17,960
was the program
for the unification of German workers' parties.

1437
01:03:17,960 --> 01:03:21,420
Marx, when criticizing
the unification program of these parties,

1438
01:03:21,420 --> 01:03:24,300
Expounded much more
about socialism.

1439
01:03:24,300 --> 01:03:26,870
So, he talks about:
a dictatorship of the proletariat,

1440
01:03:26,930 --> 01:03:29,980
the first phase of communism,
the higher stage of communism,

1441
01:03:29,980 --> 01:03:31,520
talks about the role of the State.

1442
01:03:31,520 --> 01:03:35,200
He talks about the period
of transition from socialism to communism.

1443
01:03:35,200 --> 01:03:38,020
This book is very important;
it's short, too. Very short.

1444
01:03:38,020 --> 01:03:39,300
And then, moving on
to Lenin.

1445
01:03:39,300 --> 01:03:41,260
People say all the time:
“read Lenin, read Lenin!”

1446
01:03:41,260 --> 01:03:42,180
Let's read Lenin then,
shall we?

1447
01:03:42,180 --> 01:03:43,820
First book:
“What is to be done?”.

1448
01:03:43,820 --> 01:03:46,820
What is to the done? is a book
that Lenin writes in 1902,

1449
01:03:46,820 --> 01:03:50,980
for the Second Congress
of the Russian Social Democratic Labor Party.

1450
01:03:50,980 --> 01:03:54,620
Lenin was part of a party at that time,
the Russian Social Democratic Workers' Party,

1451
01:03:54,670 --> 01:03:57,880
